INSERT INTO `chapters` VALUES (1,1,9,1,'The sky over Ashton Lane was gray, as though it too had questions. Bob Carter, a retired private investigator, had just returned from the market with a bag of groceries when he saw it—a nondescript brown package resting on his porch. There was no label. No name. No return address. Just a thin black string tied around it in a perfect bow.\n\nHe looked both ways down the quiet suburban street. Nothing but the usual stillness. The neighbors were either out or too busy to care. Bob’s instincts prickled. Years of investigating frauds, murders, and disappearances had sharpened his senses beyond the average man. Something about this package was off. It didn’t belong here.\n\nHe picked it up cautiously, feeling the weight—light, too light for it to be a book or tools. He brought it inside and placed it on the kitchen table, eyeing it like it might detonate. After a beat, he untied the string, unfolded the brown paper, and discovered... a single photograph.\n\nIt was black and white, clearly old, maybe from the 1960s. A group of people stood in front of a large brick building—an orphanage, judging by the worn-out signage. Bob’s eyes scanned the photo. He didn’t recognize anyone at first. Then he noticed someone in the back, slightly blurred but unmistakable.\n\nIt was him.\n\nA younger version of Bob, maybe in his twenties, wearing a leather jacket and a half-smile. He remembered that photo. It was taken in front of the Ellensworth Home for Orphans. He hadn’t been there in decades. And he hadn’t told anyone about that chapter of his life.\n\nOn the back of the photo was a single sentence, written in neat block letters:\n\n“You forgot something, Robert.”\n\nHe sat down slowly. The use of “Robert” made it feel more serious. Only people from his past ever called him that. His heart began to thump louder.\n\nHe took out his phone and dialed Mark Talbot, his old partner at the precinct. Mark had stayed in law enforcement after Bob retired. If anyone could trace the origin of an anonymous package, it was him.\n\n“Bob? You okay?” Mark answered quickly.\n\n“I think someone from my past is trying to reach out—oddly.” He described the package, the photo, and the message.\n\n“Ellensworth,” Mark said, repeating the name slowly. “Didn’t that place burn down twenty years ago?”\n\nBob blinked. “Burn down? I thought it was shut down.”\n\n“No, arson. It was all over the news. Three dead, cause never confirmed. Never caught the arsonist either. You didn’t know?”\n\nBob’s mind spun. “No. I left town just before then. I never looked back.”\n\n“Well,” Mark said with a sigh, “maybe it’s time you did.”\n\nThat night, Bob couldn’t sleep. He stared at the photo for hours. Why now? Why him? And who sent the package?\n\nThe next morning, he packed a small bag, grabbed his coat, and started his car. There was only one way to find answers.\n\nHe was going back to Ellensworth.','2025-04-01 12:07:36','2025-07-12 18:08:03'),(2,1,9,2,'The journey back to Ellensworth was somber. The town hadn’t changed much—same crooked fences, same tired trees lining the road. But the orphanage, once a beacon for lost children, was now a blackened skeleton of brick and memory.\n\nBob stood at the rusted gate, staring at the overgrown lot. Weeds crawled through the broken pavement like nature trying to forget. The sign was half-charred, but still legible: Ellensworth Home for Children.\n\nInside, rubble crunched under his boots. Char marks streaked the walls like old scars. He crouched near a corner where the old study used to be. Something shimmered—half-buried under soot—a small metal locket.\n\nInside the locket was a faded photo of a girl—Lena. Bob remembered her. Smart. Quiet. Always writing in her little blue notebook.\n\nHe heard footsteps.\n\nSpinning around, he found himself face-to-face with a woman in her thirties.\n\n“You shouldn’t be here,” she said coldly.\n\n“And you are?”\n\n“Clara Hart. Town historian. I maintain records of sites like this.”\n\nBob raised an eyebrow. “Do your records mention who died in the fire?”\n\nShe hesitated. “Three children. Names unconfirmed.”\n\n“Lena?” he asked.\n\nShe paled. “That name’s not in the files. Why do you know it?”\n\nBob hesitated. “She was close to me… before I left.”\n\nClara gave a measured nod. “Be careful. People don’t dig here for a reason.”\n\nShe left without another word.\n\nThat night, Bob found a motel. He placed the photo and locket on the table. The photo still taunted him—who sent it? Why now?\n\nHe flipped it again. New handwriting had appeared beneath the old message:\n“Start with the one who stayed.”','2025-04-01 12:07:36','2025-07-12 18:10:31'),(3,1,9,3,'Bob drove back to Ashton and found Mark at the police archives, flipping through faded folders. Mark hadn’t aged well—gray, tired, eyes filled with ghosts.\n\n“You knew more than you let on,” Bob accused.\n\nMark sighed. “I tried to protect you, Bob.”\n\n“From what?”\n\n“From yourself. From the truth.”\n\nBob threw the photo onto the desk. “Recognize this?”\n\nMark nodded. “Yeah. That day… the last group photo.”\n\nBob’s tone sharpened. “Who died in the fire?”\n\nMark hesitated. “Lena, for sure. A boy named Danny. And the third… we never confirmed.”\n\n“You didn’t tell me Lena died.”\n\n“You were gone, Bob. You left and never looked back.”\n\nBob clenched his fists. “I need her file.”\n\nMark sighed and unlocked a drawer. Inside were three folders, brittle from time.\n\nLena’s file was nearly empty. Just her date of arrival, age eight. No birth certificate. No family. Her only possession: a blue notebook. Missing from evidence.\n\nBob skimmed Danny’s file. Nothing unusual—except a final note in red ink: “Said he saw someone leave the night of the fire. Died the next day.”\n\nSomeone had silenced Danny.\n\nBob looked at Mark. “Who else had access to these?”\n\nMark stared at the floor. “One name: Father Hensley. The head caretaker.”\n\nBob’s eyes narrowed. “Is he still alive?”\n\nMark nodded. “Runs a small chapel just outside town. Lives alone.”\n\nBob grabbed his coat. “Then he’s next.”','2025-04-01 12:07:36','2025-07-12 18:10:58'),(4,1,7,4,'The chapel was quiet, nestled between old oaks and forgotten graves. Father Hensley, now in his seventies, looked frail but alert.\n\nBob didn’t waste time. “You remember me?”\n\n“I remember all of you,” Hensley said, his voice gravelly.\n\n“Tell me about the fire.”\n\nHensley looked away. “Some truths are heavier than others.”\n\n“Start talking,” Bob growled.\n\nThe priest sighed. “There were rumors Lena had discovered something. About one of the staff. She wouldn’t say who. Just wrote in that notebook.”\n\nBob’s voice trembled. “What happened to it?”\n\n“I locked it in the study safe… then the fire.”\n\n“You think someone started it to destroy the notebook?”\n\nHensley nodded. “Lena was brave. Too brave. Someone got scared.”\n\n“Who?”\n\nHensley paused, then whispered, “Clara Hart.”\n\nBob reeled. “The historian?”\n\n“She was a volunteer back then. Had access. She and Lena argued days before the fire. I didn’t think much of it. But the next day, Lena cried for hours. Said someone threatened her.”\n\n“Why didn’t you go to the police?”\n\n“I tried. But the fire happened first. The files were pulled from my hands. And Clara? She vanished for years… until she returned last spring.”\n\nBob stood, rage coiling. “She’s been watching.”\n\nHensley handed him a key. “The safe might still be intact under the rubble. Bring her truth back.”','2025-04-01 12:07:36','2025-07-12 18:11:37'),(5,1,7,5,'At sunrise, Bob returned to the ruins. Guided by memory, he found the corner where the study once stood.\n\nHe dug for hours—removing stone, ash, broken timber—until his fingers struck cold metal. The old floor safe, rusted but intact.\n\nThe key clicked.\n\nInside, wrapped in a plastic sheet, was Lena’s blue notebook.\n\nHe flipped through trembling pages. Drawings. Names. Notes. Symbols. One name repeated with growing urgency:\n“CH.”\n\nClara Hart.\n\nThe final entry chilled him:\n“She said she’d burn it all. If I tell, I’ll disappear like Danny.”\n\nBob stared in silence. He wasn’t ready for the next part—but he had no choice.\n\nSuddenly, a shadow crossed his path.\n\n“Looking for secrets, Robert?” Clara stood behind him, a pistol in hand.\n\n“You killed them,” he said bitterly.\n\nHer face was cold. “Lena knew too much. She would’ve ruined everything. You leaving made it easier.”\n\nBob’s voice shook. “You threatened a child.”\n\n“She found my ledger. Money stolen. Names. You were a fool for coming back.”\n\nBob held up the notebook. “This goes to the police.”\n\n“Not if I stop you.”\n\nA shout rang out.\n\nMark stepped into view, gun drawn. “Drop it, Clara.”\n\nFor a moment, time froze.\n\nThen Clara laughed, wild and bitter, and raised her gun—only to be tackled by Mark.\n\nIt was over.','2025-04-01 12:07:36','2025-07-12 18:12:04'),(6,1,9,6,'At the station, Clara’s confession unraveled years of silence. Embezzlement. Cover-ups. And finally, arson to erase the evidence.\n\nLena had tried to stop her. Danny had seen Clara at the orphanage the night of the fire. Clara had silenced them both.\n\nThe town reeled as headlines spread: Local Historian Charged in Cold Case Arson Murders.\n\nBob stood outside the courtroom weeks later, notebook in hand. Mark joined him.\n\n“She’ll get life,” Mark said. “Justice finally came.”\n\nBob nodded. “Lena deserved that.”\n\n“What will you do now?”\n\nBob looked at the horizon. “Start over. Maybe write this down.”\n\nMark chuckled. “Detective turned author?”\n\n“Why not? Truth deserves to be remembered.”\n\nAs they walked away, a breeze flipped the notebook open.\n\nPage 1:\n“For Robert. If you ever come back… follow the truth.”','2025-04-01 12:07:36','2025-07-12 18:12:33'),(7,1,7,7,'Months later, Bob sat at his desk, pen in hand. He was writing again—something he hadn’t done in years.\n\nThe manuscript title: “Ashes of Ellensworth.”\n\nA package arrived one afternoon. This time, it was labeled.\n\nInside: another photo. A child—Lena—smiling brightly. Alongside, a letter.\n\nDear Bob,\nThank you for not forgetting me.\nSome people live in the shadows. You brought light back.\nTell our story. So others won’t be scared to speak.\n–Lena\n\nTears welled in his eyes.\n\nHe placed the photo on the mantel, beside the locket. A soft peace settled over him.\n\nFor the first time in years, Bob felt whole.\n\nThe mystery had ended—but the truth would live on.','2025-04-01 12:07:36','2025-07-12 18:12:57'),(8,2,4,1,'Emma always felt drawn to the abandoned lavender garden near her cottage...','2025-04-01 12:21:08','2025-04-01 12:21:08'),(9,2,4,2,'Following the glowing lavender path, Emma discovered an ancient stone door...','2025-04-01 12:21:08','2025-04-01 12:21:08'),(10,2,5,3,'A mystical figure emerged—a guardian of the garden...','2025-04-01 12:21:08','2025-04-01 12:21:08'),(11,2,5,4,'Emma raced to the garden’s center, where a crystal pulsed beneath ancient roots...','2025-04-01 12:21:08','2025-04-01 12:21:08'),(12,21,24,1,'hi this is the very first draft from user 11111','2025-06-04 12:55:23','2025-06-04 12:55:23'),(13,23,24,1,'again test 1','2025-06-04 13:36:37','2025-06-05 20:51:49'),(16,24,24,1,'testing 2','2025-06-04 13:41:49','2025-06-04 13:41:49'),(17,25,24,1,'aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa\nbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbbb\ncccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccc','2025-06-04 13:48:06','2025-06-04 13:48:06'),(18,26,24,1,'test 4 chapter 1','2025-06-04 13:50:55','2025-06-04 13:51:05'),(20,27,24,1,'test 5 chapter 1','2025-06-04 13:55:26','2025-06-04 13:55:26'),(21,27,24,2,'test 5 chapter 2','2025-06-04 13:55:40','2025-06-04 13:55:40'),(22,27,24,3,'test 5 chapter 3','2025-06-04 13:55:53','2025-06-04 13:55:53'),(23,28,24,1,'test 6 chapter 1','2025-06-04 14:00:08','2025-06-04 14:00:08'),(24,28,24,2,'test 6 chapter 2','2025-06-04 14:00:20','2025-06-04 14:00:20'),(25,28,24,3,'test 6 chapter 3','2025-06-04 14:00:35','20