 c1','2025-06-13 16:01:05','2025-06-13 16:01:05'),(59,46,27,2,'Fi c2','2025-06-13 16:01:14','2025-06-13 16:01:14'),(60,46,27,3,'Fi c3','2025-06-13 16:01:23','2025-06-13 16:01:23'),(61,46,27,5,'fi c5','2025-06-13 16:02:00','2025-06-13 16:02:00'),(62,45,27,3,'f c3','2025-06-13 16:02:44','2025-06-13 16:02:53'),(64,47,27,1,'s c1','2025-06-13 16:10:27','2025-06-13 16:10:27'),(65,47,27,3,'s c3 from read book','2025-06-13 16:11:02','2025-06-13 16:11:02'),(66,47,27,2,'s c222','2025-06-13 16:11:16','2025-06-13 16:38:41'),(67,47,24,5,'from co_author fixed by the author','2025-06-13 16:34:11','2025-06-13 16:39:00'),(71,47,24,4,'from co_author fixed by the author','2025-06-13 16:39:24','2025-06-13 16:39:24'),(72,47,27,6,'draft6','2025-06-13 16:44:20','2025-06-13 16:44:20'),(73,41,24,6,'no cover','2025-06-14 10:06:29','2025-06-14 10:06:29'),(74,48,24,1,'no cover 2 c11','2025-06-14 10:32:10','2025-06-14 10:32:59'),(75,48,24,2,'no cover 2 c2','2025-06-14 10:32:29','2025-06-14 10:32:29'),(77,49,24,1,'no c3 c11','2025-06-14 10:40:34','2025-06-14 10:47:35'),(79,49,24,3,'no cover 3 c3','2025-06-14 11:13:12','2025-06-14 11:13:12'),(80,50,24,1,'nc c1','2025-06-14 11:27:06','2025-06-14 11:27:06'),(81,50,24,2,'nc c4','2025-06-14 11:27:20','2025-06-14 11:27:20'),(82,50,24,3,'nc c3','2025-06-14 11:27:28','2025-06-14 11:27:28'),(83,50,24,4,'nc c4 updated just now','2025-06-14 11:27:35','2025-06-14 11:27:59'),(85,51,26,1,'w c1 update','2025-06-14 11:39:14','2025-06-14 11:39:52'),(86,51,26,2,'white 1 c2','2025-06-14 11:39:26','2025-06-14 11:39:26'),(88,51,26,4,'w c4','2025-06-14 11:40:26','2025-06-14 11:40:26'),(89,51,26,3,'w1 c3 draft','2025-06-14 11:40:41','2025-06-14 11:40:41'),(90,51,26,7,'w2 c','2025-06-14 11:48:16','2025-06-14 11:48:16'),(91,52,27,1,'black c1','2025-06-14 12:01:29','2025-06-14 12:01:29'),(92,52,27,2,'black c2','2025-06-14 12:01:37','2025-06-14 12:01:37'),(93,52,27,5,'black 5','2025-06-14 12:02:59','2025-06-14 12:02:59'),(94,52,27,4,'black 4 draft','2025-06-14 12:03:10','2025-06-14 12:03:10'),(95,53,27,1,'black 2 c1','2025-06-14 12:03:47','2025-06-14 12:03:47'),(96,54,24,1,'The Whisper Room\n-------------------------------\nThey called it Room Five.\n\nEvery door in Westwood Dorm had been opened—except one. Painted shut, padlocked, even bricked behind a shelf. But everyone whispered about it.\n\n“Someone screamed in there once,” said Jenny, the RA.\n\n“People disappear,” added Mark, her roommate.\n\nLena didn’t believe in ghost stories. She was new, skeptical, and curious. So, late one night, she sneaked out, flashlight in hand. The hallway felt colder than usual. The flickering lights above buzzed like whispers.\n\nShe stood before the sealed room, heart thumping. The number 5 was barely visible under layers of peeling paint. Her fingers tingled as she touched the doorknob—rusted shut.\n\nSuddenly, it clicked.\n\nThe lock… had just opened by itself.\n\nShe staggered back, but the door creaked open an inch, as if inviting her. From inside came the unmistakable sound of breathing. Heavy. Slow.\n\nShe leaned forward, trying to see.\n\nSilence.\n\nThen—\n\nA whisper.\n\n“Come in.”\n\nShe ran.','2025-06-28 19:56:34','2025-06-28 19:58:18'),(97,54,24,2,'Mirror Faces\nLena tried to tell Jenny, but she laughed it off. “You were just dreaming. That door hasn’t opened in decades.”\n\nBut Lena knew what she saw.\n\nThat night, the whispers returned. But now, they were everywhere—in the vents, behind the walls, in the mirror.\n\nAs she brushed her teeth, the bathroom mirror fogged over from steam. Words formed slowly:\n\n“You opened it.”\n\nShe wiped it away, only to find something else—her reflection wasn\'t matching her movements. It smiled when she didn’t. It blinked too late. She stepped back.\n\nHer reflection whispered: “Room Five is yours now.”\n\nThe lights flickered. Behind her, a shadow moved across the shower curtain. But when she turned, nothing was there.\n\nLena slept with the light on.\n\nBut she couldn’t stop the dreams—always the same hallway, always the fifth door opening wider.','2025-06-28 19:56:52','2025-06-28 19:56:52'),(98,54,24,3,'The Missing Ones\n------------------------\nThe next morning, Mark was gone.\n\nNo one had seen him leave. His phone, books, and jacket were still in his room. His bed untouched.\n\nThen it happened again.\n\nSasha from 2B. Then the tall kid from the cafeteria. Three students gone within a week. No forced entry. No noise. Just gone.\n\nLena scoured the internet. There had been eight disappearances in the past ten years from Westwood Dorm. All unsolved.\n\nThey had one thing in common: all stayed on the west hall, near Room Five.\n\nShe returned to the door—this time with a camera.\n\nThe door opened before she even touched it.\n\nInside, dust floated in the air like snow. The room was completely empty. No furniture. No bed. Just four blank walls.\n\nThen she realized—there were five walls.\n\nThe fifth wall had no window. No exit. Only a full-length mirror—and in it, Mark stood silently, staring back.','2025-06-28 19:57:17','2025-06-28 19:57:17'),(99,54,24,4,'Don’t Look Too Long\n------------------------------\nLena blinked. The mirror image didn’t.\n\nShe stepped closer. Mark looked pale, lost—his mouth opened like he wanted to scream, but no sound came out. Behind him, in the reflection, shadows moved.\n\nShe turned. The real room was empty.\n\nWhen she turned back to the mirror—she was in it. Looking into the dorm from the other side.\n\nNo sound. No escape.\n\nShe banged on the glass, but it echoed like stone. Mark grabbed her arm. “You looked too long,” he mouthed. “Now you’re one of us.”\n\nIn the real world, Lena’s body went still, eyes glazed. To everyone else, she had just collapsed. The nurse said she fainted. But her friends couldn’t wake her.\n\nInside the mirror, Lena watched the real world move on without her.\n\nShe wasn’t the last.','2025-06-28 19:57:40','2025-06-28 19:57:40'),(101,55,26,1,'The Ticking Room\n----------------------------\nEvelyn stumbled into the antique store to escape the rain, her umbrella nearly turning inside out in the wind. The store smelled of old paper and forgotten dreams. She wandered between shelves of curiosities until she heard a rhythmic ticking that seemed to call her name. At the back of the store was a small door, slightly ajar, leading to a dim room full of clocks.\n\nClocks of every kind lined the walls—pendulum clocks, pocket watches, cuckoo clocks—all ticking in perfect harmony. In the middle sat an old man with silver spectacles and a kind smile. He adjusted gears with delicate tools.\n\n“These clocks don’t just tell time,” he said without looking up. “They remember it.”\n\nOne particular watch caught her eye—a gold one, dusty and still. “Why doesn’t it tick?” she asked.\n\n“It’s waiting,” he replied cryptically.\n\nFor what, he didn’t say.\n\nEvelyn returned the next day, and the next. Something about the place felt alive, and the golden watch whispered to her with its silence.','2025-06-29 21:29:23','2025-06-29 21:29:23'),(102,55,26,2,'Time Unwound\n-------------------------------\nOn the fourth visit, Evelyn couldn\'t resist. She gently picked up the golden watch. The moment her fingers wrapped around it, the air shimmered. The room dissolved, and suddenly she was standing on a cobbled street in the middle of a war-torn city, smoke rising in the distance.\n\nPeople rushed past in clothes from another era. Sirens wailed. A woman nearby screamed, “Emile!”—then vanished. Evelyn’s heart pounded.\n\nThe watch was showing her a memory.\n\nShe let go and fell backward, landing on the wooden floor of the clock room. Gasping, she looked at the watch in her hand, which now ticked softly.\n\nThe clockmaker appeared beside her, calm as ever. “Time reveals truth to those who listen.”\n\n“Was that... real?” Evelyn asked.\n\n“It was a moment that mattered, once,” he said. “Sometimes, time invites us to understand before we move forward.”\n\nShe stared at the watch, the ticking now syncing with her heartbeat. Something inside her had shifted.','2025-06-29 21:29:53','2025-06-29 21:29:53'),(103,56,24,1,'The Static Message\n----------------------------------\nThe radio room was unusually silent except for the low hum of the machines. Jared Ross, a graveyard shift technician at Station 94.3, had worked hundreds of late nights, tuning signals and adjusting frequencies. But tonight, something felt… off.\n\nAs he rotated the dial to filter out static, a new signal bled through. It wasn’t a broadcast — it was a whisper. Then a series of numbers.\n\n“Delta-7… Sierra-1… Terminate.”\n\nJared froze. He leaned in, adjusting the gain to get a clearer sound. The message repeated.\n\n“Delta-7… Sierra-1… Terminate.”\n\nHe recorded it, heart racing. It didn’t match any known transmission code. Before he could alert anyone, the station lights flickered. A thud echoed behind the service door.\n\n“Who\'s there?” he called out.\n\nNo reply.\n\nHe saved the audio to a USB, slipped it into his pocket, and locked the broadcast room. But the hallway lights were out now. And in the darkness, Jared could feel he wasn’t alone.','2025-06-29 21:37:32','2025-06-29 21:37:32'),(104,56,24,2,'The Red Folder\n-------------------------------\nJared didn’t go home. He drove straight to his friend Mia\'s apartment — a former data analyst with connections to the underground signal surveillance networks. She listened to the audio and paled.\n\n“This isn’t a random signal,” she whispered. “It’s a kill code. These are real targets.”\n\nMia pulled out a red folder from her old security case. Inside were classified names and files — operations tagged “Deep Echo.”\n\nJared’s name was on the list.\n\n“You’ve been marked,” Mia said. “And if you heard that signal, they know you did.”\n\nThey barely had time to process it before Mia’s window shattered. A dart embedded in her wall. They hit the floor. Jared grabbed the USB and folder, dragging Mia into the stairwell.\n\nSirens sounded outside, but it wasn’t the police.\n\n“We need to vanish,” Jared said. “And fast.”','2025-06-29 21:37:59','2025-06-29 21:37:59'),(105,56,24,3,'The Man in Gray\n----------------------------\nBy morning, they were off-grid in an abandoned train yard. Jared studied the names in the red folder. A few were crossed out. Others were still “active.”\n\nThey needed answers.\n\nThat’s when the man in gray appeared — tall, emotionless, and clearly trained. He didn’t pull a weapon. He handed Jared a burner phone.\n\n“You have 72 hours,” he said. “Deliver the folder to Vault Seven or everyone on that list dies.”\n\n“Why us?” Jared asked.\n\nThe man paused. “You were never supposed to hear it. But now, you\'re part of the protocol.”\n\nThen he vanished between rusted freight cars.\n\nMia powered on the phone. One GPS coordinate. Northern forestland — no roads, no data signal.\n\nA setup, or a chance to end this?\n\nJared chose to go.','2025-06-29 21:38:25','2025-06-29 21:38:25'),(106,56,24,4,'Vault Seven\n----------------------------\nAfter hours of hiking, they found a camouflaged entrance carved into a cliff face. “Vault Seven” was etched into the concrete wall.\n\nInside, cold air and humming tech welcomed them.\n\nJared placed the folder on a sensor pad. Lights turned green. A voice boomed:\n\n“Transfer acknowledged. Integrity breach detected. Engaging purge.”\n\nMetal doors sealed behind them.\n\nScreens lit up with every name on the kill list. Red marks blinked beside several.\n\nThen Jared saw a live feed — of him. Inside the vault.\n\n“We’ve been lured into a coffin,” Mia muttered.\n\nBut Jared spotted a maintenance panel. He jammed the vault override. Alarms blared. A countdown started.\n\n“Ten seconds,” the voice warned.\n\nThey ran — barely making it out before the vault exploded behind them.','2025-06-29 21:38:50','2025-06-29 21:38:50'),(110,58,26,1,'The Moonborn Gift \n-------------------------------------\nLiora had always felt strange under the moonlight. While others slept, she wandered the forest, where the trees whispered her name. On her sixteenth birthday, a silver mark bloomed on her palm—the Moonmark, a gift seen once in a generation. Her village elder paled when he saw it. “You’re the chosen, Liora. The stars have named you.” That night, the moon hung low and bright, bathing the woods in silver. Liora followed its light to a hidden grove she\'d never seen before. At the center stood a tree with glowing roots, and a boy no older than her, dressed in robes of twilight. “I’ve waited centuries,” he said, eyes shining with stardust. “You must awaken the grove, or the magic of this world will die.” The tree pulsed with energy. The wind carried ancient songs. The stars, once distant, now watched her closely.','2025-06-29 23:28:29','2025-06-29 23:28:29'),(111,58,26,2,'The Grove Awakens \n------------------------------------\nThe boy called himself Caelen, last of the starbound. “This grove was once sacred. Now it sleeps.” Liora touched the glowing bark, and warmth surged through her veins. Her Moonmark pulsed. All around, the grove came alive—petals unfurling, vines trembling, light spinning like fireflies. Caelen handed her a crystal vial. “The grove’s heart must be taken to the Celestial Spire before the next lunar eclipse. Or the darkness wins.” Liora had never left her village, but something in her stirred—courage, perhaps. As she stepped away from the grove, shadows followed. Creatures called the Umbra, made of smoke and hunger, sensed her rise. “They’ll hunt you now,” Caelen warned. “The stars chose you, but the darkness never forgets.” That night, Liora’s dreams burned with images of a shattered sky, a black sun, and herself, standing at the edge of the world—alone but glowing with moonlight.','2025-06-29 23:28:57','2025-06-29 23:28:57'),(112,58,26,3,'Wings of Windfire \n--------------------------\nLiora and Caelen journeyed beyond the valley, through mountains that hummed with old magic. At dusk, they reached the Windfire Cliffs, home to the last skybeast—Aera, a dragon woven from mist and flame. She tested Liora with riddles and a gust strong enough to flatten trees. “What shines brightest but never burns?” Liora whispered, “Hope.” Aera smiled. “Then ride.” On dragonback, they soared toward the Celestial Spire, stars guiding them like fireflies. But the Umbra attacked mid-flight—shadowy tendrils grasping from storm clouds. Caelen conjured shields of light while Liora reached into herself, her Moonmark blinding. She whispered the grove’s lullaby, and a beam of starlight blasted through the darkness, tearing the sky open. The Umbra fell back. “You are more than chosen,” Caelen said breathlessly. “You are becoming.” Below, the Spire waited, tall as dreams, ancient as the first light.','2025-06-29 23:29:31','2025-06-29 23:29:31'),(113,59,34,1,'g','2025-06-30 03:30:42','2025-06-30 03:30:42'),(114,59,34,2,'2','2025-06-30 03:30:54','2025-06-30 03:30:54'),(115,58,24,5,'hhhhhhhhhhhhhh','2025-06-30 05:07:53','2025-06-30 05:07:53'),(116,60,26,1,'hhhhhhh','2025-06-30 05:18:46','2025-06-30 05:18:46'),(125,62,24,1,'In the kingdom of Velmira, magic was outlawed. Ever since the Sorcerer Wars ended, enchantments were hunted, and mystical creatures were either destroyed or locked away.\n\nTalia was a servant girl in the citadel, with calloused hands and a quiet soul. Her only comfort was the small, blue-glowing butterfly she kept in a jar under her bed.\n\nShe’d found it as a child, hiding in the ruins near the forbidden forest. No one knew. She whispered to it every night. It never spoke back—until her sixteenth birthday.\n\nAs the bells of midnight rang, the butterfly shimmered.\n\nAnd then it spoke.\n\n“You are not who you think you are.”','2025-07-12 19:52:13','2025-07-12 19:52:13'),(126,62,24,2,'Talia’s heart thundered. The butterfly, glowing with sapphire light, flapped once—and her room exploded in color.\n\nMemories poured into her head—not hers, but a life she had forgotten.\n\nShe was the daughter of a Skyweaver, a people who could speak to butterflies—creatures of ancient power who guarded the threads of fate.\n\nHer mother had caged her magic to protect her during the war. The butterfly was her guardian, bound to her by ancient spell.\n\n\"You were hidden in plain sight,\" the creature whispered. \"But the spell is fading.\"\n\nSuddenly, a cold wind swept through the castle.\n\nThe butterfly flapped in panic.\n\n“They’ve found us.”','2025-07-12 19:52:36','2025-07-12 19:52:36');
