Hidden Chamber – They race against time...','c_7.png'),(23,3,2,'2025-04-01 18:35:11',1,'The Midnight Escape','Chapter 1: The Forbidden Park – The friends sneak into an abandoned amusement park...\nChapter 2: The Escape – Realizing the park’s eerie powers...','c_8.png'),(25,3,3,'2025-04-01 18:35:11',6,'The Lost Key','Chapter 1: The Key in the Park – The three friends stumble upon an old key...\nChapter 2: The Hidden Doorway – The friends open the door to a magical world...','c_9.png'),(27,4,6,'2025-04-01 18:41:59',3,'Shattered Alibis','Chapter 1: The Accusation – Claire takes on the case of a man accused of a high-profile murder.\nChapter 2: Unraveling the Truth – Claire uncovers conflicting evidence...','c_10.png'),(29,4,7,'2025-04-01 18:41:59',2,'Crimson Lies','Chapter 1: The Robbery – Detective Carter investigates a robbery...\nChapter 2: The Trail of Lies – Alex uncovers a series of connections...\nChapter 3: Confronting the Truth – Alex faces a betrayal...',NULL),(32,4,8,'2025-04-01 18:41:59',1,'The Silent Witness','Chapter 1: The First Murder – Jenna is assigned to a case that seems like an open-and-shut murder...',NULL),(34,1,24,'2025-06-07 19:44:56',2,'book no 2','book 2 des','c_2.png'),(35,1,24,'2025-06-07 19:55:29',1,'book 1','book 1 d','c_1.png'),(37,2,24,'2025-06-07 20:10:52',2,'2','22','c_6.png'),(38,2,24,'2025-06-07 20:16:37',1,'3','33','c_3.png'),(39,3,24,'2025-06-08 07:09:19',1,'8','88','c_5.png'),(40,4,24,'2025-06-08 07:20:12',0,'8c','crime horror',NULL),(41,4,24,'2025-06-08 07:20:42',0,'10','10','c_10.png'),(42,4,24,'2025-06-08 07:36:24',0,'test','test',NULL),(43,3,24,'2025-06-08 08:38:26',0,'youth fiction 1','111',NULL),(44,3,24,'2025-06-08 08:54:18',0,'you','yout',NULL),(45,2,24,'2025-06-08 10:48:13',2,'test 1','test 11',NULL),(46,3,24,'2025-06-08 10:51:22',0,'test 2','test 22',NULL),(47,2,24,'2025-06-08 10:53:29',1,'test 3','test 33',NULL),(48,1,24,'2025-06-08 11:01:21',1,'test 3','test 33',NULL),(49,4,24,'2025-06-08 11:04:07',0,'crime horror 1','ch',NULL),(50,4,24,'2025-06-08 11:11:06',0,'crime horror 2','crime horror2',NULL),(51,1,24,'2025-06-08 11:17:40',0,'fantasy 1','fantasy1',NULL),(52,1,24,'2025-06-08 11:20:17',0,'fantasy 2','fantasy 2',NULL),(53,1,24,'2025-06-08 11:23:19',0,'fantasy 3','fantasy 3',NULL),(54,1,24,'2025-06-08 11:23:48',0,'fantasy 4','fantasy 4',NULL),(55,2,24,'2025-06-08 12:21:09',0,'photo test','photo test','fantasy.png'),(56,2,24,'2025-06-08 12:28:48',0,'photo test2','photo test','fantasy.png'),(57,2,24,'2025-06-08 12:31:34',1,'photo test 3','3','ccp_1.png'),(58,1,24,'2025-06-08 12:32:11',0,'photo test','f','ccp_2.png'),(59,3,24,'2025-06-08 13:54:42',0,'photo test','photo test','ccp_3.png'),(60,4,27,'2025-06-08 14:12:44',2,'testing 305','305 \nchapter 1\nchapter 2','ccp_4.png'),(61,2,27,'2025-06-08 14:13:53',1,'code name 333','333','ccp_5.png'),(62,2,27,'2025-06-08 14:41:05',0,'photo crop testing','pct','ccp_6.png'),(63,3,26,'2025-06-08 14:53:14',0,'crop photo testing','cpt 2','ccp_7.png'),(64,3,24,'2025-06-14 14:18:56',0,'T','T1',NULL),(65,3,28,'2025-06-14 14:30:14',0,'$4','my first contest entry','ccp_8.png'),(66,4,28,'2025-06-14 14:43:34',0,'1','1',NULL),(67,2,28,'2025-06-14 14:44:04',0,'33','2',NULL),(68,2,2,'2025-06-22 06:12:30',0,'1test','1','°Рисуем в нейросети_°Иллюстрации_Клипарт_Промты_.jpg'),(69,2,6,'2025-06-22 19:08:27',5,'The Disappearing Light','Chapter 1: The Power Cut\nIt began with a blackout. Just past 11 p.m., the entire street plunged into darkness. Claire stood at her window, heart racing. The storm outside had raged for hours, but this silence felt unnatural. Across the street, Mr. Harold\'s porch light flickered, then died. Suddenly, a shadow darted across the sidewalk. Claire stepped back, breathing heavily. This wasn’t just a power failure—it felt like a warning. Grabbing her flashlight, she tiptoed to the basement, where the fuse box hummed. Just as she reached for the switch, a cold hand clamped down on her shoulder. She froze. The air smelled metallic. Turning around, no one was there. Only silence. She backed away slowly. Upstairs, the floorboards creaked. Someone was in the house. She turned off the flashlight and hid behind the furnace, clutching her phone with trembling fingers. No service. The darkness wasn’t empty—it was watching.\n\nChapter 2: Footsteps\nClaire held her breath as footsteps echoed above. Slow. Heavy. Deliberate. Her mind raced—was it a burglar, or something worse? A drawer opened upstairs. The intruder wasn’t searching quietly. Claire’s eyes scanned the basement, landing on her dad’s old crowbar. She crept to it, grasping the cold iron. Another step. Then two. The stairs creaked. Someone was coming down. Claire tucked into the shadows, heart pounding like a drum. The flashlight beam returned—this time not hers. It scanned the room, inching closer. The light paused, right over her. She gripped the crowbar. A deep voice spoke, “I know you’re here.” Claire sprang up, swinging. The flashlight dropped, crashing to the floor. She bolted past him, up the stairs, ignoring the yell behind her. Upstairs, the storm had stopped. But outside her window, a van with its engine running waited in the rain.\n\nChapter 3: The Van\nClaire didn’t stop to think. She slammed the front door behind her and ran into the rain. The van’s headlights blinded her for a moment. The driver’s side opened. A man stepped out—tall, soaked, wearing black gloves. Claire darted into the bushes. He called out, “Claire? Come on, we’re late.” Her blood froze. How did he know her name? She crawled farther into the hedge, clutching her phone. Still no signal. The man got back into the van but didn’t leave. He was waiting. Watching. She couldn’t go back inside, not with the intruder down there. Just then, a second shadow approached the van—from the alley. They exchanged words too low to hear. Claire used the distraction to run, barefoot, down the street. She didn’t stop until she reached Mrs. Ellie\'s house. Lights were on. Claire rang the bell. No answer. She turned. The van was now parked outside.\n\nChapter 4: The Letter\nMrs. Ellie’s door creaked open—unlocked. Claire entered slowly. “Hello?” No response. Her wet feet left prints on the wooden floor. The TV buzzed static. A mug of tea sat untouched on the table. Something felt off. On the counter, a note: “Claire, if you’re reading this, don’t trust the police. He’s one of them.” Claire’s breath caught. Was this for her? Who wrote it? She flipped the page. “They’re watching you. Meet me at the lighthouse. Midnight.” Signed: E. Claire backed toward the door. A thud came from the hallway. She ducked into the pantry just as a figure stepped into the kitchen. Through the cracks, she saw the glint of a badge. A police officer. Her heart pounded. Was he the one from the van? The officer walked around slowly, calling her name softly. Claire stayed silent. Midnight was three hours away. Could she survive until then?\n\nChapter 5: The Escape\nAs the officer searched, Claire spotted an old cellar door in the pantry floor. She quietly pulled it open and climbed down, careful not to let it slam. The darkness below smelled of dust and oil. She felt her way forward until she found a narrow exit—leading to the backyard shed. The rain had stopped. The van was gone. She made a run for it, cutting through alleys until she reached her father’s workshop. It had been locked since his death last year. But Claire remembered the code: 0423—his badge number. Inside, dusty blueprints, a hidden safe, and folders. She opened one marked “Project Light.” Inside: maps, photos of the town, and surveillance images—of her. One showed her from tonight. She stared in horror. A noise at the door. Someone was trying to open it. She slammed the folder shut and backed away, crowbar in hand.\n\nChapter 6: Project Light\nA voice called through the door. “Claire. Please. I’m not here to hurt you.” She didn’t recognize it. “I worked with your father. He knew they were coming. He tried to stop it.” Claire hesitated. “What’s Project Light?” she asked. Silence. Then, “It’s not a project. It’s a person. You.” The door creaked open slowly. A woman entered, hands raised. “I’m Ellie. The real one.” Claire stepped back. “I saw the note.” Ellie nodded. “He used to call you Light. You’re the only one who can expose them.” She handed Claire a flash drive. “Everything is here. But they know. You have until midnight. The lighthouse is the only safe signal zone left.” Claire took it, hand trembling. “What if they find me?” Ellie smiled grimly. “They already have.” Tires screeched outside. Lights blazed through the windows. The hunt was on. Claire bolted out the back door, drive in hand.\n\nChapter 7: The Lighthouse\nThe old lighthouse stood at the edge of the cliff, surrounded by crashing waves and wind. Claire reached it at 11:57 p.m. Her lungs burned. The flash drive felt hot in her hand. Inside, the beacon room was cold and damp. A terminal flickered to life as she plugged the drive in. Files loaded: names, operations, recordings—evidence of decades of corruption. Suddenly, footsteps echoed behind her. A man in uniform stepped in. “End of the line,” he said. “Your father was warned. Now it’s your turn.” Claire hit SEND. The files uploaded to a secure public server. Too late now. The man raised his weapon. A shot rang out—but not from him. He fell. Behind him, Ellie held the gun. “Told you I’d watch your back.” The beacon lit up, cutting through the fog. Sirens wailed in the distance. Claire had exposed the truth. The light was no longer disappearing.','ccp_9.png'),(70,2,12,'2025-06-22 19:27:42',1,'Echoes in the Ward','Chapter 1: Room 606\nNina entered St. Augustine’s Psychiatric Ward as part of her final year psychology internship. Assigned to file old patient records, she was told never to enter Room 606. Naturally, that’s where her curiosity took her. The door was sealed shut, rusted around the lock. But on the clipboard outside, she read: Patient: Evelyn Moss. Diagnosis: None. Status: Observed. The last note dated back 18 years. As she turned to leave, she heard it—three soft knocks from inside the room. Frozen, Nina stared at the door. Then again—three knocks. No one was supposed to be in there. She ran to the nurse’s station, asking about Evelyn. The head nurse went pale. “That room’s been empty for decades,” she whispered. “We don’t talk about Evelyn.” That night, in her dorm, Nina found a sticky note on her door. It read: You opened the door, now she knows your name.\n\nChapter 2: Evelyn’s Whisper\nSleep was impossible. Every time Nina closed her eyes, she heard a whisper. Faint. Repeating her name. Nina... Nina... The heater clicked on. The air turned cold. She sat up, scanning the room. Nothing. But her mirror was fogged—words written from the inside: Let me out. The next day, she confronted the head nurse. “Who was Evelyn Moss?” The nurse whispered, “She wasn’t sick. She was a key. A vessel.” That night, Nina snuck into the records room. The file had been shredded, but one photo remained. A girl with pale skin, eyes completely black. Scribbled beneath it: She’s still listening. Suddenly, all the lights went out. The air felt suffocating. From the dark corridor, a soft humming rose—a lullaby. Something moved past the records shelf. She bolted, but the door slammed shut behind her. In the silence, Evelyn whispered: It’s your turn now, Nina.\n\nChapter 3: The Black Tape\nThe janitor, a mute man named Gregor, found her trembling the next morning. “You were lucky,” the nurse said. “Most don’t make it through the night in that room.” Nina insisted she saw something—heard Evelyn. They dismissed her. Until she found the black cassette tape hidden in her locker. Labeled: “606: First Recording.” She found an old player and listened. A girl’s voice: “They keep me locked away. But I remember everything. They said I’m a danger to minds. But minds are easy to break.” The recording warped, then: “Nina, you’re just like me.” She dropped the tape. It cracked, oozing black fluid. Nina backed away. Gregor saw the mess and looked terrified. He scribbled a note: Don’t listen to the second tape. But there was no second tape… right? That night, one appeared on her pillow. Same black casing. Label: “606: Transfer Initiated.”\n\nChapter 4: Silent Screams\nNina burned the second tape. She watched it melt in the sink. The black ooze steamed and hissed. Still, that night, she had the dream. She was strapped to a hospital bed, Evelyn standing over her, eyes pure black, lips unmoving. Yet Nina heard: “Let’s switch now.” Waking in sweat, she found bruises on her wrists—like restraints had held her down. The staff noticed changes. Nina was quieter, eyes darker. She couldn’t explain it, even to herself. Her handwriting changed. Her memories blurred. Gregor cornered her in the corridor, showing an old photo: Evelyn as a teen—and someone standing beside her who looked exactly like Nina. But that was impossible. “She was waiting,” Gregor signed. “For a host. For you.” The mirrors began cracking when Nina passed. Lights flickered. She couldn’t sleep anymore. Evelyn was pushing closer. Her reflection now smiled back—when she didn’t.\n\nChapter 5: The Switch\nNina decided to end it. She returned to Room 606, crowbar in hand. She pried the door open. Inside, the room was pristine—untouched by time. A single chair, and a mirror bolted to the wall. Nothing else. She stepped in. The door closed behind her. In the mirror, Evelyn stood—not beside her, in place of her. The reflection spoke: “Now you understand. I never left. I was just waiting to be remembered.” Nina shouted, but no sound came. Her voice didn’t work. The real Nina watched as Evelyn smiled through her body—her own hands, her own eyes now moving without her. She was trapped. Inside the mirror. On the ward’s camera, staff saw Nina exit the room, calm, collected. Her eyes now pitch black. She signed the discharge papers. Evelyn walked free. And in Room 606, the mirror cracked... revealing Nina’s silent scream forever frozen inside.\n\nChapter 6: The New Patient\nTwo weeks later, a new intern arrived. The head nurse smiled politely. “You’ll be helping with storage. But one rule: stay away from Room 606.” The intern, curious, passed by the room anyway. The door was sealed—again. Clipboard blank. But as she leaned in, she heard soft humming. And three gentle knocks from inside. She shivered, walking away. In the mirror at the end of the hallway, a second reflection followed her. Behind the glass in Room 606, Nina stared. Her scream couldn’t escape. Her story couldn’t be told. But Evelyn’s could. And now, she was writing new chapters. One patient at a time.','ccp_10.png'),(71,2,30,'2025-06-22 19:34:08',4,'The Last Train South','Chapter 1: Final Departure\nMaya boarded the 10:46 p.m. southbound train from Platform 13. The station was unusually empty, despite the last-train rush. The conductor, tall and pale, barely looked at her as she passed. Her seat—Car B, Row 3—was empty. So was the entire car. As the train pulled away, the city lights vanished unnaturally fast. Fog thickened outside the windows. Maya texted her sister: \"On board. Strange vibe.\" No response. She turned to ask the conductor a question—but he was gone. Every car she passed was empty. No passengers. No crew. Just silence. Then the intercom crackled: “Next stop: Mercy Crossing.” She froze. That wasn’t a real station. She had never heard of it. Her phone died. A note fluttered from above her seat. In neat cursive: “You shouldn’t have come alone.” The lights flickered. The train picked up speed. Outside, she saw only dark woods.\n\nChapter 2: Mercy Crossing\nThe train jerked violently, throwing Maya from her seat. The lights dimmed to red emergency mode. The announcement repeated: “Approaching Mercy Crossing. Please remain seated.” Maya ran toward the nearest door, but it wouldn’t open. Outside, the forest gave way to mist-shrouded ruins. She spotted figures—motionless, lining the track. Not passengers. Not human. One turned. It had no eyes. Just a carved, gaping smile. The train screeched to a halt. Maya backed away as the figures began boarding. Their skin looked painted. They filed in silently, taking random seats. None looked at her. Then one did. It tilted its head and whispered, “This train runs on memory.” Maya’s breath caught. “What does that mean?” she asked. But the thing simply replied, “Yours is the last one.” Before she could react, the doors slammed shut. The train began moving again. The passengers all turned to face her in unison.\n\nChapter 3: Car B\nMaya locked herself in the restroom. Her heart pounded as she pressed her ear to the metal door. No sounds. No voices. Just the low hum of the train. When she emerged, all passengers were gone again. Only she remained. But the train looked different now—older, rusted, with flickering lights and peeling seats. On the wall, she saw faded graffiti: “WE NEVER GOT OFF.” She stumbled back into her seat and found a small cassette recorder on the tray. Pressing play, she heard her own voice: “If you’re listening to this… I didn’t make it off.” It continued: “You’ll see your memories before the end. Don’t believe them. Especially the girl.” Maya dropped the recorder. She didn’t remember ever saying that. She turned—and saw a child in the next row. Same eyes, same hair. The child smiled and whispered: “Let’s remember together.”\n\nChapter 4: The Memory Car\nThe child led Maya to the front of the train. Doors she couldn’t open earlier now swung freely. Inside, a movie reel flickered to life, showing Maya’s childhood. Then her sister’s funeral. Then her own accident—one she had no memory of. “You died,” the child whispered. “You just didn’t accept it.” Maya screamed. “I’m alive! I boarded this train!” The child touched her arm. Suddenly, Maya stood in her apartment, reliving her last morning—coffee, messages, rush to the train. But in the bathroom mirror that morning, her reflection hadn’t looked back. She hadn’t noticed. Now she did. The illusion shattered. Maya dropped to her knees in the train. “Why?” she asked. “Because the train helps us let go,” the child said. The passengers returned, now somber, gently watching her. The train slowed once more. Ahead: a glowing station bathed in soft light. The real last stop.\n\nChapter 5: The Conductor’s Choice\nThe conductor returned—face no longer pale, but serene. “You remembered,” he said softly. “Few do.” Maya stood, uncertain. “Where does this train go now?” He smiled. “Where it always does. Back to collect the lost.” As the doors opened at the glowing station, Maya hesitated. “Can I go back?” The child shook her head. “You already did. Every night. Until you saw the truth.” Maya stepped off. The air was warm, peaceful. Behind her, the train vanished into fog. Somewhere, in another city, someone else boarded the 10:46 southbound—alone. The cycle began again. But this time, Maya watched from the platform, no longer a passenger, but a guide. The last train south never truly ends. It only waits—for the next soul to remember.','ccp_11.png'),(72,2,31,'2025-06-22 19:38:14',3,'The Apartment Above','Chapter 1: Thumps at 3 A.M.\nEmma moved into her new apartment on the fifth floor, glad for independence. The rent was cheap, and the building was quiet—too quiet. The landlord casually said, “There’s no sixth floor, just a sealed attic.” Yet every night, at exactly 3 a.m., she heard loud thumps coming from above. Furniture scraping. Footsteps pacing. Once, even a soft cry. She asked the neighbor across the hall, an old woman named Mrs. Delarue, about it. The woman simply said, “Ignore it. Never knock back.” But one night, fed up, Emma grabbed a broom and banged on the ceiling. Silence followed—eerily calm. Then, precisely three minutes later, came three slow knocks from above. Heavy. Measured. Like a response. Her lights flickered. Then her phone rang—unknown number. When she answered, a child’s voice whispered, “Why did you wake me?” The call ended. Her ceiling cracked slightly, and dust fell.\n\nChapter 2: The Sixth Floor\nEmma couldn’t sleep. The knocking never returned—but now, the shadows in her room felt heavier. She checked the stairwell the next day and found something strange: the button for Floor 6 had been crudely pried off the elevator. Only five floors were supposed to exist. That evening, she followed a maintenance worker and asked about the top floor. He frowned. “There is no sixth floor. The building was designed with one, but it was sealed after… something happened.” He refused to say more. Back in her apartment, Emma used a broomstick to tap upward—six quick knocks. Immediately, she heard whispering from the ceiling. A chill ran down her spine. She turned to her door. Someone had slid a photo under it. A black-and-white image of a girl staring through an attic vent. On the back, in shaky writing: “She’s still there.” That night, the thumping returned.\n\nChapter 3: The Journal\nDetermined, Emma checked the building\'s archives at the public library. She found an old news clipping from 1982: “Child Found Dead in Sixth Floor Apartment—Parents Missing.” No names were listed. Back home, she returned to the storage space above her closet, where she\'d earlier noticed loose boards. Behind the wall insulation, she found a leather-bound journal. Inside were drawings—dark, frantic sketches of eyes and hands. The entries were from a girl named Lily. “They locked me in. They said the shadows would eat me. They lied. They became the shadows.” The last entry was almost illegible: “I’m not alone anymore. She whispers too.” That night, Emma dreamt of Lily—silent, pale, pointing upward. When Emma woke, her apartment door was wide open, and muddy child-sized footprints led to the ceiling vent. From inside, something breathed. Slowly. Waiting.\n\nChapter 4: The Vent\nEmma grabbed a flashlight and chair, unscrewing the ceiling vent. Dust choked her as she peeked inside. Beyond the duct was a narrow crawlspace leading toward the building’s top. Curiosity overpowering fear, she crawled in. The metal floor groaned beneath her. After ten minutes of crawling, she emerged into an attic-like space—Room 601, hidden above her apartment. Old toys, a crib, and moldy wallpaper surrounded her. In the corner sat a child’s mattress. Drawings covered the walls: “No light,” “Don’t knock,” “She walks backward.” Emma found an old mirror covered with cloth. She lifted it. Behind her, the reflection showed a girl standing—but when she turned around, no one was there. The mirror cracked. A whisper filled the room: “You saw me. Now I can follow.” Emma screamed and fled. But as she re-entered her apartment, she noticed a new drawing on her wall: her—sleeping.\n\nChapter 5: Don’t Wake Her\nEmma tried to leave the building. The elevator buttons glitched. The stairs led her back to the same floor every time. At 3 a.m., her apartment turned cold. Her reflection no longer moved in sync. She smashed the mirror—but her reflection kept staring. Desperate, she called Mrs. Delarue. The old woman sighed. “You shouldn’t have climbed. That floor was sealed for a reason.” Emma begged, “How do I stop it?” The woman whispered, “You can’t. Just don’t let her wake fully.” Emma locked every door and stayed awake all night. But exhaustion won. She fell asleep around 2:59 a.m. And then—three soft knocks. She opened her eyes. Standing at the foot of her bed was the girl—Lily. Except… her eyes were wrong. Not sad. Not scared. Hungry. She whispered, “Thanks for letting me in.” The lights went out.\n\nChapter 6: The New Tenant\nWeeks later, the apartment was listed for rent again. “Great view, very affordable,” said the agent. A young man moved in. On his first night, he asked about the attic noises. “Old pipes,” the landlord said. That night, at 3 a.m., came the thumping. He knocked the ceiling once in annoyance. Then again. Just to be funny. Then… silence. The power flickered. His phone vibrated. Unknown number: “Why did you wake me?” He laughed nervously. A faint giggle came from the vent above. When he turned off the lights, the reflection in the TV screen showed two people. He was alone. But she never was. Above him, Room 601 waited. And Lily smiled in the dark.','ccp_12.png'),(73,2,32,'2025-06-22 19:42:58',3,'The Sound of Glass','Chapter 1: Cracked\nAva worked as a night cleaner at the city museum. Quiet. Routine. Until the exhibit of antique mirrors arrived. One cracked mirror stood out—it didn’t reflect properly. Instead of her full body, it always showed her turned away. Her manager joked, “Probably cursed,” and moved on. But every night, Ava saw something move behind her reflection. A figure, dressed like her, but always five seconds late. One night, the reflection turned its head—before Ava did. She dropped her mop. The mirror cracked deeper. From that moment, strange things happened. Glasses in the café shattered when she walked by. Light bulbs burst. One night, her phone recorded a voice: “You cracked it open. Now I see too.” Her reflection no longer copied her. It watched her. Then smiled. When Ava blinked, her reflection didn’t. That’s when she stopped looking into any glass at all.\n\nChapter 2: Room of Mirrors\nThe museum’s power went out the next night. Ava was alone. The mirror exhibit glowed faintly, though unplugged. She crept closer. The cracked mirror now reflected a room—not the one she stood in. Inside the reflection, dozens of Ava’s stood in identical poses. But one in the back slowly raised its hand and waved. Ava didn’t move. Her chest tightened. Suddenly, she heard a tap-tap-tap from behind the glass. The sound of glass fingernails. Then a whisper from behind her: “Closer.” She turned, nothing there. But in the mirror, one version of her began walking forward—closer to the glass. Its eyes were missing. Instead, deep black holes. When she stepped back, the mirror vibrated. One by one, other mirrors cracked around her. A storm of reflections, all out of sync. They whispered, in unison: “The real one must break.” Ava ran. But her reflection stayed.\n\nChapter 3: Shatterpoint\nAva decided to destroy the cracked mirror. She grabbed a hammer from the maintenance shed. But when she returned, the mirror was gone. A note on the exhibit wall read: “Donated to Room 413.” But the museum only had 4 floors. Confused, Ava descended to the basement—where unused exhibit pieces were stored. Room 413 had no key, only a padlock with symbols instead of numbers. On the wall next to it: a sketch of her own face. She entered the combination instinctively. Inside: a massive mirror wall, with one cracked panel in the center. As she approached, her reflection was already there—smiling. “It’s your turn,” it whispered. Then reached through. Ava screamed as her feet locked in place. Her skin numbed. Her reflection stepped out, smoothing its new body. “Real enough,” it said. Ava’s voice echoed inside the glass, now trapped. Her eyes turned black.\n\nChapter 4: The Exhibit\nThe museum reopened the next day. “The Reflection Room” was the new attraction. Visitors walked through smiling, taking selfies. But if you stayed past closing, the reflections stayed too long. Moved when you didn’t. Smiled at things you hadn’t noticed. And sometimes, if you looked close enough, one mirror didn’t reflect the exhibit at all—it showed a girl screaming behind glass. No one heard her. Only the sound of faint tapping. The cracked mirror sat in the middle of the display. Its label read: “Don’t Look Too Long.” People thought it was a joke. But late at night, after the janitor swept the floors and silence returned, a voice would whisper behind the glass: “Your turn is coming.” And somewhere inside, Ava still watched. And waited.','ccp_13.png'),(74,1,26,'2025-06-22 19:51:40',6,'The Feather of Fire','Chapter 1: Ember\'s Secret\nEmber always burned hotter than others. Not just temper—her skin sparked flames when she felt fear. She kept gloves on, always. But after saving a falling hawk with flaming hands, she found a golden feather in her palm. It whispered, \"Ignite.\" That night, her window glowed red. Something ancient was calling her name.\n\nChapter 2: The Phoenix Mark\nThe golden feather melted into her skin, branding her wrist with fire. Ember felt no pain—only clarity. Flames obeyed her now. She hid it from her father, but the forest near town burned a perfect circle. Villagers murmured of Phoenix magic. Ember wasn’t the only one watching the flames. A hunter in a dark cloak followed.\n\nChapter 3: Trial by Flame\nThe hunter found her by the river, where steam rose from her footprints. “The Phoenix chose you,” he said. “But fire tests loyalty.” He lit a torch and handed her a map of the Dead Peaks. “Go there. Alone.” Ember accepted. At midnight, fire leapt from her hands like wings. She didn’t walk—she flew.\n\nChapter 4: Ash Spirits\nThe Dead Peaks moaned with wind. Ember\'s fire dimmed. Shadows circled—ash spirits, memories of failed Phoenix heirs. They whispered doubts, clawed her mind. Ember fell to her knees. But then she remembered the hawk, its faith. Her fire reignited—not from rage, but resolve. The spirits fled. She passed the trial. The sky welcomed her.\n\nChapter 5: Rise, Phoenix\nAt the summit, the original Phoenix circled overhead—massive, golden, eternal. “You kept compassion,” it said. “Others kept power.” It burst into flame, diving into her chest. Ember gasped. Wings of fire spread from her back. She was no longer hiding. The world would remember the Phoenix. And she, Ember, would burn away the darkness.','ccp_14.png'),(75,1,27,'2025-06-22 19:59:36',3,'The Last Leaf of Elwyn','Chapter 1: Autumn Never Ends\nIn Elwyn, autumn never ended. Leaves fell, gold and red, endlessly. The last green tree stood in silence. Sylas, a young druid, guarded it. One day, a leaf shimmered silver and dropped. Sylas caught it. It pulsed like a heartbeat. The wind spoke, “Plant me in the frostlands.” Sylas set out before the snow came.\n\nChapter 2: The Frostlands\nSnow blinded him. Wolves circled. Sylas whispered to the silver leaf, and vines burst from the ground, shielding him. He reached the heart of the Frostlands—ice fields cracked like glass. He planted the leaf. The ground trembled. A green sprout pierced through the ice. Life returned. But something beneath the frost stirred. Eyes opened.\n\nChapter 3: The Waking Cold\nA giant of ice emerged—ancient and angry. “You break my slumber with spring?” it roared. Sylas stood firm. “Elwyn dies if this doesn’t grow.” The giant raised its blade. But the sprout shimmered, transforming into a tree of stars. The cold faded. The giant wept, turned to frost, and slept once more. Peace returned.\n\nChapter 4: Elwyn Blooms Again\nBack in Elwyn, the silver leaf’s magic spread. Trees bloomed green. Autumn broke. Children danced in sun-warmed meadows. Sylas stood beneath the new Star Tree, leaves glowing in many colors. “You listened to the wind,” it whispered. “So we live.” Elwyn breathed again. And Sylas became the first Guardian of the Seasons.','ccp_15.png'),(76,1,28,'2025-06-22 20:01:38',1,'The Clockmaker’s Dragon','Chapter 1: Broken Wings\nJorah, a clockmaker’s apprentice, found a strange gear in the market—etched with scales. That night, he fit it into a broken model dragon. Sparks flew. Gears turned. The dragon blinked. “Where’s my fire?” it asked. Jorah dropped his wrench. It was alive. The gear pulsed. Somewhere, someone else felt it stir. They were not friendly.\n\nChapter 2: Gears and Flames\nThe dragon, named Crix, couldn’t breathe fire. “You must find my core,” it said. Jorah found old blueprints in the attic. A map of the Sky Foundry—now abandoned. Clockwork knights guarded its secrets. Jorah and Crix set off by steam glider. Every turn of Crix’s gears felt warmer. Time was ticking. Enemies followed.\n\nChapter 3: Sky Foundry\nThe Foundry rose above clouds, floating on iron wings. Crix trembled. “It began here.” They entered. Machines still moved, long-forgotten. In the center, a core chamber glowed. But a masked man blocked them—Ashbinder, the one who stole Crix’s heart. “You fixed him,” he sneered. “I’ll break him again.” Crix growled. Jorah tightened his grip.\n\nChapter 4: Clockwork War\nAshbinder summoned broken dragons—metal, monstrous. Crix fought, gears grinding, wings blazing. Jorah reached the heart chamber, restored the core. Light burst from Crix’s chest. Fire roared. The enemy melted. The Foundry began to collapse. Jorah jumped on Crix’s back. “Time to fly,” Crix said. They soared through smoke, leaving ruin behind. The sky applauded.\n\nChapter 5: Sparks of Tomorrow\nBack in the city, Jorah opened a new shop: “Crix & Co. – Wonders Repaired.” Kids brought broken toys, dreams, and ideas. Crix perched above the door, glowing. “Where now?” it asked. Jorah smiled. “Wherever time dares us.” Magic and metal had made peace. And in the clockmaker’s hands, the future ticked stronger.','ccp_16.png'),(77,1,29,'2025-06-22 20:03:25',4,'The Invisible Prince','Chapter 1: No One Remembers\nIn the kingdom of Veyr, one prince vanished—forgotten by all. Except himself. Prince Cael wandered unseen, unheard, a ghost in sunlight. A curse erased him from memory. His name dissolved. Only the royal dog wagged its tail when he passed. He vowed to reclaim his throne, even if no one remembered who he was.\n\nChapter 2: A Witch in Red\nCael found a witch who remembered. “I cast the curse, but not for gold,” she said. “Your kindness saved me once. But your father ordered my death.” She offered him a mirror. “Find your name. Speak it aloud under moonlight.” He left, grateful. The mirror showed shadows. And a crown, burning.\n\nChapter 3: The Three Names\nHe journeyed to three ruins: one whispered Sable, another Ryn, the last Cael. Each name twisted the mirror’s glow. Under the moon, he spoke: “Cael, son of fire, heir of ash.” Light burst from his chest. His body shimmered. Voices gasped. He was visible. Remembered. But the kingdom had changed.\n\nChapter 4: The Ash King\nThe king had died. His brother ruled now—cold and cruel. “Who are you?” the new king laughed. Cael stepped forward. The royal dog barked and bowed. A storm of fire symbols circled Cael’s head. “The forgotten prince,” Cael said. Magic roared behind him. The throne knew its true master. The ash crown returned.\n\nChapter 5: Remember My Name\nCael ruled with wisdom, always wearing a simple ring: three names engraved. “I remember the silence,” he said. “So I’ll listen to the quietest voices.” Statues rose of him across Veyr. Not of power—but of memory. And when people forgot things, they whispered to the wind. The wind always whispered back: “Cael remembers.”','ccp_17.png'),(78,1,30,'2025-06-22 20:05:57',2,'The Floating Library','Chapter 1: Books That Fly\nNila chased a book into the sky. It flapped like a bird and vanished into a cloud. A ladder descended. She climbed. Above the clouds floated a massive library—held by balloons, wind, and wonder. Librarians in robes welcomed her. “You followed knowledge,” they said. “You may read. But books here read you back.”\n\nChapter 2: Shelves of Memory\nEvery book Nila opened showed her past—pages turning with forgotten thoughts. One book wept. Another laughed. The oldest book showed a blank page. “Write here,” the librarian said. “And the library may keep you.” That night, the wind howled. A storm approached. The books flapped nervously. Something was coming to steal them.\n\nChapter 3: The Ink Thief\nA shadow ship struck the floating library—sucking ink, stealing stories. Nila grabbed a glowing quill. “Not this time.” She wrote a story so powerful it burst into light. The shadow vanished. The books cheered. The library hovered steady again. Nila earned a robe. “Write more,” they said. “Write truth.” And so she did.\n\nChapter 4: A Story Worth Flying For\nYears later, people on Earth would glimpse a shape in the sky—pages, sails, words glowing. The Floating Library still soared. And every once in a while, a falling book would land near a child dreaming under stars. A story would begin. And when it did, so would another ladder.','ccp_18.png'),(79,3,31,'2025-06-22 20:18:27',2,'The Locker Letters','Chapter 1: Note #1\nCassie found a sticky note in her locker: \"You\'re braver than yesterday.\" She looked around. No one noticed. It wasn’t signed. The next day, another appeared: \"Speak up. Someone will listen.\" Cassie hadn’t told anyone about her stage fright. Somehow, someone knew. She didn’t feel alone anymore. She started talking again—in class. And smiling.\n\nChapter 2: Rumors and Roses\nA rumor spread: Cassie liked Mr. Gray, the gym teacher. False, but embarrassing. She wanted to hide. But inside her locker: \"Roses bloom after thorns. Walk tall.\" A small rose sticker was attached. She looked at her classmates differently now. One of them was her anonymous friend. Someone kind was still watching.\n\nChapter 3: The Slip\nCassie slipped during her class speech. Laughter erupted. Her face burned. At her locker: \"Falling means you\'re moving forward.\" She smiled for the first time that day. Later, someone bumped into her—Sarah from art club. “Loved your speech,” she said. “Funny and real.” Cassie looked closer. A rose sticker peeked from Sarah’s notebook.\n\nChapter 4: Found\nCassie left her own note in Sarah’s locker: \"Thank you for every sticky word.\" The next day, Sarah waved her over. “Want to start a kindness wall?” she asked. Cassie nodded. By week’s end, the wall bloomed with notes, stickers, and smiles. No one knew who wrote which. But everyone felt seen.\n\nChapter 5: The Ripple\nCassie wrote daily now. Notes for shy kids. Lonely ones. Angry ones. The wall grew. The laughter changed. Kinder. The locker notes didn’t stop problems—but they started hope. Cassie never found out who left the first note. But every time she helped someone else stand, she thought: Maybe we all can be the first note.','ccp_19.png'),(80,3,32,'2025-06-22 20:21:45',4,'Hoodie Season','Chapter 1: The Hoodie\nJaden always wore a hoodie—black, oversized, zipped tight. He called it armor. People called it weird. New student Maya asked, “Is it that cold?” He said nothing. But she kept sitting with him at lunch. Shared her fries. Told jokes. She didn’t ask more. She waited. Jaden felt less invisible under his hoodie.\n\nChapter 2: Stained\nA drink spilled on Jaden’s hoodie. Panic. It hid everything—scars, shame, secrets. He ran to the bathroom. Maya followed. “You’re not broken,” she said quietly. “You’re just... stitched different.” He cried. Not loud. Just enough to breathe again. He returned to class with the stained hoodie. Nobody laughed. Maya smiled. He stayed.\n\nChapter 3: Brave Threads\nJaden started designing hoodies—drawing symbols on the sleeves. A quiet sun. A small phoenix. Maya wore one proudly. Then others asked too. Soon, he ran an online shop: Brave Threads. His hoodie wasn’t armor anymore. It was art. It still hid parts—but now told stories. And others wore them with pride.\n\nChapter 4: Hoodie Off\nThe day he spoke in front of the class, Jaden wore a T-shirt. First time ever. Nervous. Sweaty. But loud. “Sometimes, we hide not to disappear, but to heal.” Applause. The hoodie lay on his chair. He’d still wear it, sure. But it no longer wore him.','ccp_20.png'),(81,3,27,'2025-06-22 20:23:16',3,'The Summer Bus','Chapter 1: Route 15\nThe summer bus ran only from June to August. Lila called it her escape ride. Same seat, same driver, same boredom. Until Leo boarded. Red headphones, sketchpad, awkward smile. “Mind if I draw you?” he asked. She blinked. “Weird. Okay.” That ride didn’t feel boring. Neither did the next one.\n\nChapter 2: Corners and Questions\nLila learned Leo moved every summer. New town. New people. Always temporary. “Do you get tired of leaving?” she asked. “No,” he said. “I get tired of never being missed.” So Lila made a deal: one secret shared per stop. By week’s end, they had seventeen. And a nickname: Bus Besties.\n\nChapter 3: Rain Stop\nIt rained. Hard. The bus got delayed. Lila and Leo played truth-or-dare. She dared him to show his worst sketch. He showed a drawing of himself, face scribbled out. “It’s how I feel sometimes,” he said. She took his hand. “I see your face. It’s worth drawing.” He smiled, face uncovered.\n\nChapter 4: Summer’s End\nAugust came too fast. Leo’s family was leaving again. Lila cried on the bus. He handed her a sketchbook. “Every day of this summer,” he said. “Draw something back. Mail it.” He gave her an envelope. Then he was gone. The bus felt empty. But the sketchbook was full—of hope.\n\nChapter 5: Return Ticket\nNext summer, the bus doors opened. Lila sat alone—until Leo stepped on, taller, grinning. “Seat taken?” She shook her head, holding up her sketchbook. “Got one more page left.” He sat beside her. “Draw me again?” She laughed. “Not just you. Us.” Route 15 rolled on. Summer began again.','ccp_21.png'),(82,3,29,'2025-06-22 20:26:16',0,'The Quiet Club','Chapter 1: The Sign\nA hand-drawn flyer said: “Join The Quiet Club. No talking. Just thinking. Room 104.” Sam, tired of noisy clubs, went. Inside: beanbags, sketchpads, calming music. Only three kids. All silent. It was... peaceful. He stayed an hour. No one spoke. Still, he left feeling heard.\n\nChapter 2: Unspoken Rules\nNo phones. No noise. Just expression. Some drew. Others journaled. One kid stacked cards silently. Every week, more joined. Room 104 stayed quiet—but full. Sam painted clouds. A girl wrote haikus. A boy read comics. Nobody had to perform. Nobody had to explain. Quiet became power, not absence.\n\nChapter 3: Loud Days\nOne day, a fire drill broke their meeting. Chaos, noise, shouting. Sam panicked. Outside, the club members gathered under a tree. They didn’t speak—but handed each other pages, poems, and pictures. Silence returned. Calm followed. They rebuilt the club’s peace. Together.\n\nChapter 4: Quiet Shouts Back\nTheir school newspaper mocked them: “The Awkward Club.” Sam made a poster: “Silence is strength.” Dozens signed it. The paper printed an apology. The club grew. They got their own room—bigger, brighter. Still silent. Still strong.\n\nChapter 5: A Place to Breathe\nYears later, Sam visited Room 104 again. New students now. Still quiet. Still drawing, writing, building peace. He smiled. Left a note on the door: “Thanks for letting us be ourselves, even without words.”','ccp_22.png'),(83,3,33,'2025-06-22 20:32:38',1,'Kicks and Kindness','Chapter 1: The Shoes\nDanny wore torn sneakers. Kids teased him. Until coach handed him a surprise—brand new cleats. “Someone donated them,” he said. Danny played soccer like lightning. But he wanted to know who helped. Every game, he looked into the stands. Always saw one person cheering: quiet Liam, from science club.\n\nChapter 2: Benched\nDanny found Liam in the library. “Was it you?” Liam blushed. “You run like fire. Fire deserves shoes.” Danny laughed. “Come to practice.” Liam refused. “I’m not a player.” Danny said, “You helped me play. That counts.” They fist-bumped. Next game, Liam brought snacks. He stayed.\n\nChapter 3: Match Day\nA bully shoved Liam. “You’re not a real teammate.” Danny stepped in. “He’s realer than anyone.” Coach nodded. “True players protect more than the goal.” The team rallied around Liam. That day, they won 4–2. Not just because of kicks—but kindness.\n\nChapter 4: New Captain\nDanny was voted captain. He handed the badge to Liam. “This belongs to both of us.” Liam wore it proudly. The field felt different now—fairer. Louder. Better. Sometimes, it takes one small kindness to change the whole game.','ccp_23.png'),(84,4,33,'2025-06-22 20:40:28',2,'The Red Door','Chapter 1: 4B Is Missing\nApartment 4B had been sealed for years. Rumors said the last tenant vanished—left dinner on the table. Detective Reina got a call: “Screams. Blood.” From a child’s voice. No one had lived there in a decade. She opened the red door. The lights flickered. The apartment smelled like iron. The table still had food.\n\nChapter 2: Scratches in the Floor\nInside 4B, Reina found deep scratches across the wooden floor. From inside to the door—as if something tried to escape. The phone in the hallway rang. She answered. “He’s still hungry.” A child’s voice. Static. Silence. In the fridge: a missing person’s flyer. But the face was hers. The year said 1999.\n\nChapter 3: The Tooth in the Sink\nWater wouldn’t stop running in the bathroom. Reina turned it off. Something rolled from the drain. A tooth. Human. She backed away. The mirror fogged on its own. Then letters appeared: \"JOIN US.\" The door slammed shut. Her radio buzzed. Headquarters said, “Detective Reina? You died here twenty-five years ago. Who are we talking to?”\n\nChapter 4: The Dinner Returns\nShe ran. Every door led back to 4B. Her dinner now on the plate. Still warm. Footsteps circled her. Shadows crawled along the walls. The red door opened again—but from the inside. Laughter spilled out. Childlike. Wrong. Then—cold hands pulled her in. One whisper before the door shut again: “It was your turn.”\n\nChapter 5: Apartment for Rent\nWeeks later, the building listed 4B for rent. Cheap. “Recently renovated,” the ad said. A couple moved in. One night, they found the mirror fogged. In red: “Hi, I’m Reina.” They never moved out. But no one saw them again. The red door remained locked… until the next voice called.','ccp_24.png'),(85,4,26,'2025-06-22 20:42:22',1,'The Man with Two Shadows','Chapter 1: Two Shadows\nCCTV footage showed the killer leaving the alley—but something was off. Two shadows followed him. One moved a second slower. Detective Leo zoomed in. The second shadow waved. The killer was never caught. But each new crime scene had one fingerprint. The same one—twice. Different positions. Same blood. Impossible. Or not.\n\nChapter 2: Split Personality\nThe killer left notes in mirror writing. “One hunts. One watches.” Psychologists assumed schizophrenia. But the wounds on victims were from two angles. Different strengths. Different patterns. As if two hands worked together. At the next crime scene, Leo saw it: two shadows on the wall. Only one person in the room.\n\nChapter 3: He’s Behind You\nA survivor gasped, “He whispered from behind—but no one was there.” Police dusted the room. The prints overlapped. Forensics were stumped. Leo stood under a flickering light, thinking. Then the bulbs shattered. His own shadow split in two. One pointed. The other reached. Something cold brushed his neck. “You see us now.”\n\nChapter 4: Mirror Room\nLeo set a trap in a mirrored chamber. The killer entered. Alone. But each mirror reflected two figures. One smiled. One wept. When the lights went out, screaming echoed. When they returned—only blood remained. The mirror closest to Leo fogged. A message appeared: “Now we are three.”','ccp_25.png'),(86,4,29,'2025-06-22 20:44:48',1,'The Dollhouse Murders','Chapter 1: Miniature Crime\nDetective Alina was sent a dollhouse. Inside—tiny furniture, blood splatter, and five clay dolls. The living room doll had a knife. A family posed at the dinner table. Hours later, a real family was found murdered. Scene matched the dollhouse exactly. The killer wasn’t playing. They were rehearsing.\n\nChapter 2: Second Dollhouse\nA week later, another package. Bedroom scene. Hanging doll. Real victim was a teenager—same position, same noose. No fingerprints. No DNA. Just perfect replicas. Alina smashed the second dollhouse. That night, her phone buzzed: “You broke the scene. Now I build you.” She found a tiny clay figure on her pillow. It looked just like her.\n\nChapter 3: Victim Preview\nAlina opened her mailbox—another dollhouse. This time, a woman stabbed in the kitchen. But the real crime hadn’t happened yet. She rushed the address—too late. But the killer left something: a dollhouse photo, now showing Alina behind the killer, frozen in clay. “You’re already part of the story,” the note said.\n\nChapter 4: The Final Scene\nAlina found the real artist—an old dollmaker. “I just sculpt what I see,” he said, trembling. “They send me visions.” In his backroom: dozens of dollhouses. Only one empty. “Yours,” he whispered. That night, Alina disappeared. In the mailroom, a box waited. Inside: a new dollhouse. One small detective inside. Forever.\n\nChapter 5: Open Viewing\nThe dollhouse was put in evidence. But guards said it rearranged itself nightly. A new hand appeared in the window each day. One doll was always waving. A smile etched deeper each time. The case remained unsolved. But no officer would touch the dollhouse again.','ccp_26.png'),(87,4,30,'2025-06-22 20:46:46',0,'The Sixth Tape','Chapter 1: Tape One\nA security guard found an old VHS tape labeled “1.” Inside: footage of an empty room. At the 2-minute mark, someone appeared suddenly. Blink—and they were gone. He died that night—face frozen in terror. Then tape “2” arrived at the police station. Same room. New victim. The background shifted each time.\n\nChapter 2: Not a Game\nEach tape ended with a number. Always a scream, then silence. Detective Kim watched Tape 3 and didn’t sleep for days. She noticed: every victim looked briefly at the camera, whispering “don’t rewind.” Tape 4 showed a girl missing since 2009. She hadn’t aged. Time didn’t pass in the room. But it recorded you.\n\nChapter 3: The Shadow Shift\nTape 5 had something else: a shadow moving frame to frame. It got closer with each second. In Tape 6, no one was in the room. But Kim saw herself in the reflection—she hadn’t filmed it. Yet, she blinked on screen. The label read: “Live Feed.” The power went out.\n\nChapter 4: Static Visit\nThe screen turned to static. Something moved behind her desk. Her phone buzzed—an old ringtone. No number. Then a single message: “You’ve been seen.” She ran to the evidence room. Tape 6 had melted. But a new tape sat inside her car. It wasn’t labeled. She burned it. But the reflection kept blinking.\n\nChapter 5: Out of Frame\nHer face no longer showed in photos. Her voice echoed on recordings—but with different words. “They’re coming.” The room from the tapes began appearing in dreams. Then waking hours. The tape wasn\'t recording anymore—it was leaking. Kim vanished. The tapes? Still arriving. Numbered. Counting down. No one knows to what.\n\nChapter 6: Tape Zero\nA new detective received “Tape 0.” Blank. But behind him, a voice whispered, “Start again.” Static filled the room. A new camera blinked on. Recording.','ccp_27.png'),(88,4,34,'2025-06-22 20:49:01',0,'The Midnight Caller','Chapter 1: Wrong Number\nLena got her first call at 12:00 a.m. exactly. “Are you alone?” a deep voice asked. She hung up. Night two: same call. “I see you.” She locked the windows. Reported it. The calls continued, always at midnight. Police traced the number—it belonged to her own landline. Disconnected for years.\n\nChapter 2: Footprints\nRain poured. Lena heard someone outside. Muddy prints led to her door—but no prints led away. The next call said, “You let me in.” She checked her security cams. At midnight, the door opened slightly. Alone. The call rang again. But now her voice answered: “He’s inside now.”\n\nChapter 3: The Basement\nLena followed strange noises to the basement. The old rotary phone rang. She lifted it. “I remember you,” said the voice. “You watched me die. You did nothing.” A case from her past. Years ago, she ignored a call for help. The victim—same voice. “Now you answer,” it growled.\n\nChapter 4: Midnight Comes\nAt 12:00 a.m., Lena disappeared. Her phone played back all her missed calls. Screams. Pleas. Regret. The police found no trace—only an unplugged phone off the hook. It rang again. Another number answered. “Are you alone?” The cycle continued.','ccp_28.png'),(89,4,24,'2025-06-28 18:23:21',2,'Red Stains','Chapter 1: The Letter\nDetective Morrow received an unsigned letter:\n\"I buried her under your floor.\"\nHis heart stopped. His wife vanished three years ago. He laughed it off—until blood seeped from the cracks near his study. The smell returned. He remembered the fight. But he’d never told anyone. The killer knew everything.\n\nChapter 2: The Eyes\nIn the morgue, every victim had eyes removed—cleanly sliced. Six bodies, one pattern. Morrow stared at the seventh—her eyes were stitched open. The coroner whispered, “They’re glass.” Inside one eye, a camera lens blinked. Someone had been watching him from the start. His reflection now smiled without moving.\n\nChapter 3: The Locked Room\nCrime scene—a locked room drenched in blood, body missing. The walls were covered in names—every unsolved case Morrow touched. At the end: “Detective Morrow – FINAL ENTRY”. The victim’s voice crackled on a recorder: “He\'s here.” A shadow passed behind Morrow. The door slammed shut. Locked from the outside.\n\nChapter 4: Red Typewriter\nA typewriter appeared in his living room, still warm. Typed words:\n\"She begged you. You watched.\"\nHe ripped the page. New line appeared:\n\"Do you remember the hotel?\"\nHe did. The Jane Doe murder. Case unsolved. He’d ignored her screams. The typewriter began typing again, keys moving on their own.\n\nChapter 5: Buried Badges\nHe dug in the forest where the bodies were supposedly buried. No graves—just police badges nailed to trees. His badge was the last. Something moved between the trees, whispering names. He turned to leave. A hand grabbed his leg from below. Fingernails broken. Face familiar. One of his victims.\n\nChapter 6: The Mask\nA figure wearing a stitched-together face mask arrived at his doorstep. “Do you believe me now?” it rasped. Morrow shot it. The mask fell—beneath, his own face stared back. In its pocket: a photo of him strangling someone. Blurry. Bloody. Timestamped. The evidence he buried had come home.\n\nChapter 7: The Confession\nMorrow turned himself in. He confessed everything—the murders, the cover-ups, the voices. But there was no record, no victims, no files. They said he’d never been a detective. Just a patient. He screamed, “Check under the floor!”\nThey did.\nNothing.\nExcept a typewriter, still warm, whispering:\n\"Start again.\"','ccp_29.png'),(90,4,35,'2025-06-28 18:25:44',3,'The Collector’s Code','Chapter 1: Missing Cases\nEvery case Detective Lyle solved was suddenly wiped from the database. Photos gone. Victims vanished. When he checked the physical files, each had a red fingerprint on the last page—his own. But he never touched them. The fingerprint ink was still wet.\n\nChapter 2: Numbered Teeth\nA victim was found with numbered teeth etched in gold. “2 of 12” written in blood. Autopsy revealed the teeth were not hers. Lyle’s phone buzzed—a text: “Next drop tonight. Count carefully.” The killer was creating a set. A complete collection.\n\nChapter 3: The Wrong House\nThey raided a suspect’s home—empty. But a room had 11 mirrors, and one showed Lyle’s childhood bedroom. He hadn’t told anyone about it. From inside the mirror, a voice whispered: “You\'re the twelfth.” Something behind the glass moved closer. His reflection didn’t follow him anymore.\n\nChapter 4: Shattered Hours\nCCTV from the crime scene showed Lyle... walking in. At 3:07 AM. Same clothes, same limp. He’d been asleep at home. He blinked. A shard of mirror lay on his nightstand, stained with blood. Someone—or something—was imitating him.\n\nChapter 5: Unmarked Graves\nHe returned to old sites, hoping for answers. In the woods, he found twelve shallow graves—eleven dug, one freshly filled. A photo fluttered nearby: him standing over a body, smiling. It was dated tomorrow.\n\nChapter 6: Face in the Crowd\nAt a press conference, Lyle saw himself in the crowd. Again. When he ran after him, everyone stared, frozen. All faces turned at once. Same face—his. The collector wasn’t hunting bodies. He was collecting identities.\n\nChapter 7: Silence in Twelve\nRoom 12. Hotel Graven. One key. Lyle entered. Inside: mirrors, a bloody typewriter, and his badge nailed to the wall. Twelve reflections grinned at him. One whispered, “You’re the last.”\nThe door shut.\nThe typewriter began.\nChapter 1: The Collector’s New Mask.','ccp_30.png'),(91,4,31,'2025-06-28 18:53:49',1,'Voices in Cell 9','Chapter 1: The Screamer\nPrisoners said Cell 9 screamed at night. But it was empty. Guard Thomsen laughed—until he heard a girl cry from inside. When he opened it, silence. Then a whisper behind him: “Thanks for letting me out.”\n\nChapter 2: The Girl in the Uniform\nA new inmate arrived, silent, in a guard’s uniform. She didn’t speak, eat, or blink. When Thomsen asked her name, she finally whispered, “You put me here.” But she’d never been booked.\n\nChapter 3: CCTV\nFootage showed her entering Cell 9—then disappearing mid-step. Another tape showed her walking backward out of the morgue. Her face glitched in every frame. No one could remember her name. Yet she appeared in everyone’s dreams.\n\nChapter 4: Marked by Nine\nThomsen found a “9” carved into his palm. Deep. Bleeding. He hadn’t noticed. More guards showed the same mark. One hanged himself, mumbling, “She never left.” They opened the morgue. The girl\'s drawer was empty.\n\nChapter 5: Unsent Letters\nThomsen found letters in his locker addressed to “Eliza.” They were from him—but he’d never written them. One letter read: “I saw what they did. I did nothing. Forgive me.” The last one had only blood prints.\n\nChapter 6: The Blackout\nThe prison went dark for 9 minutes. Screams echoed. When lights returned, nine guards were gone. The security feed was replaced by a single image: Cell 9 open. Inside: Eliza’s eyes, watching.\n\nChapter 7: Final Confession\nThomsen confessed. He’d helped cover her death—a wrongly accused girl tortured by mistake. He waited in Cell 9. At 9:09 PM, the door locked.\nEliza sat beside him.\nSmiling.\nForgiving.\nThen the cell screamed—and fell silent forever.','ccp_31.png'),(92,3,24,'2025-06-28 19:40:56',1,'The Midnight Club','Chapter 1: The Whisper\nEvery night at 12:00, a strange whisper echoed in the old school library. Lily, curious and brave, decided to stay after school to hear it for herself. She waited, heart pounding. A breeze swept through, pages rustled, and then—someone whispered her name. She wasn’t alone.\n\nChapter 2: Secret Door\nLily discovered a hidden door behind the bookshelf. She gathered her three best friends—Ray, Zara, and Ben. Together, they pushed it open. It led into a dusty tunnel. Who built this? Why? They promised to explore it every midnight and formed the “Midnight Club.”\n\nChapter 3: The Tunnel Map\nInside the tunnel, they found an old map with red markings and strange symbols. “This looks like our school... but older,” Zara whispered. They followed it to a forgotten stairwell leading under the gym. Something was down there—and it didn’t want visitors.\n\nChapter 4: Shadows Move\nThe lights flickered. Shadows moved on their own. Ben dropped his flashlight. “We should go!” he said. But Lily spotted a message: \"Find the Bell Tower.\" They weren’t just exploring anymore—they were solving a mystery. The school held a forgotten history, and it wanted to be found.\n\nChapter 5: Hidden Truths\nIn the Bell Tower, they discovered a journal from 1902. A student named Evelyn had uncovered corruption and tried to stop it—but vanished. Her ghost, still whispering, wanted justice. “She’s leading us,” Lily said. “We have to finish what she started.”\n\nChapter 6: The Final Bell\nThe club revealed the truth: Evelyn’s teacher was stealing school funds. They presented evidence to the principal. The whispering stopped. The door closed. Evelyn was at peace. The Midnight Club made a promise—to always stand for truth, even in silence. Their secret adventure was just the beginning.','ccp_32.png'),(93,3,26,'2025-06-28 19:43:01',4,'Code Green','Chapter 1: The Smell\nIt started with a bad smell. Something was wrong near the school pond. Ali noticed fish floating and plants dying. No one seemed to care. He told his best friend Mira, who agreed—Code Green, their old environment club, needed to rise again.\n\nChapter 2: Operation Clean-Up\nAli, Mira, and a few friends met in secret. Posters were made. Trash bags gathered. They called it Operation Clean-Up. Slowly, students joined. “We can make a change,” Mira said. But when they found oily water in the nearby ditch, they knew something bigger was wrong.\n\nChapter 3: The Factory Leak\nTheir science teacher helped test the water. “This isn’t normal,” she said. “It’s chemical waste.” Ali realized the nearby dye factory was leaking into the pond. But exposing them would take evidence—and courage. Code Green prepared for the hardest mission yet.\n\nChapter 4: Caught\nSneaking to the factory fence at night, Ali snapped photos. Suddenly, a flashlight beam caught him. A guard yelled. They ran. Later, shaken but safe, they reviewed the blurry photos. It was proof—but not enough. They needed an inside voice.\n\nChapter 5: The Insider\nSurprisingly, Mira’s cousin worked at the factory. After hearing the truth, he shared a shocking report. The leak had been hidden for years. With the file and photos, Code Green went to the press. Their voices were small—but growing louder.\n\nChapter 6: A New Dawn\nThe factory was fined, and cleanup began. The pond slowly healed. Code Green was no longer just a club—it was a movement. The school garden grew vegetables, rainwater was reused, and students cared again. Ali smiled. “We didn’t just save the pond. We started something.”','ccp_33.png'),(94,3,34,'2025-06-28 19:44:28',2,'Level Up, Life!','Chapter 1: Game Over\nJay lost his favorite online tournament. “You’ll never be good enough,” a teammate mocked. That night, he stared at the leaderboard. He loved gaming, but lately, real life felt like a losing game too—bad grades, no friends, and constant pressure.\n\nChapter 2: The Mentor\nMr. Rhodes, the school counselor, noticed Jay’s struggles. “Games are great,” he said. “But don’t forget to level up your real life.” He introduced Jay to a coding club. Jay hesitated. But the idea of building a game, not just playing one, excited him.\n\nChapter 3: Coding XP\nCoding was tough. Jay failed his first challenge. But unlike gaming, every failure taught something real. With help from a teammate named Saira, he created a small puzzle game. He even added a version of himself—a pixelated hero who never gave up.\n\nChapter 4: Saira’s Quest\nSaira shared her story—she once feared speaking in class, but code gave her confidence. Jay opened up too. He missed his dad, and gaming was his escape. “Let’s make something epic,” she said. “A game about healing, choices, and friendship.”\n\nChapter 5: Real-Life Boss Battle\nTheir game was selected for the school tech fair. But minutes before presenting, Jay panicked. “What if they hate it?” Saira smiled. “Then we fix it. Like always.” Together, they stood tall. Their game wasn\'t perfect—but it made people feel something.\n\nChapter 6: Level Unlocked\nJay’s game got second place—but he won something bigger: confidence, purpose, and a friend. He still gamed at night, but now he also dreamed of building worlds. Real life had its bugs, sure—but it was the only game worth mastering.','ccp_34.png'),(95,2,34,'2025-06-28 19:45:53',3,'The Vanishing Key','Chapter 1: The Locked Drawer\nNina found an old brass key in her locker, wrapped in a torn paper: “Don’t tell anyone.” She hadn’t seen this before. It didn’t fit any lock—until she tried the old janitor’s desk. The drawer opened. Inside was a photo of the principal… and a bloody glove.\n\nChapter 2: The Code Wall\nNina showed the photo to her friend Alex. Together, they found numbers scratched behind the drawer. A classroom? A locker combo? They checked Room 17—abandoned since last year’s “accident.” Someone had written: “Find the girl before he does.” What girl? Who was he?\n\nChapter 3: The Fake Fire\nThat night, the fire alarm went off. But there was no fire. Amid the confusion, Nina saw someone in a hoodie sneaking into Room 17. She followed, heart pounding. No one was there. But the blackboard now read: “Too late.”\n\nChapter 4: Missing Files\nThey broke into the school records. One file was missing—Rachel Hayes, a student who vanished last year. Her locker was sealed. The key… it clicked. Inside, they found a diary: “He knows I saw what he did. If I disappear—look in Room 22.” But Room 22 didn’t exist.\n\nChapter 5: Below the Stage\nRoom 22 was real—but hidden under the school auditorium stage. They crawled through darkness and dust. At the end of the tunnel was a wooden door. Screaming echoed behind it. “We have to open it,” Nina said. But someone was already waiting.\n\nChapter 6: The Real Villain\nThe man behind it all? Mr. Voss, the janitor. Rachel was alive—locked away for knowing his secret. He’d covered up an old murder. They rescued her, called the cops. Nina still has the key, now evidence. Some doors should stay closed—but she was glad this one opened.','ccp_35.png'),(96,2,26,'2025-06-28 19:47:49',2,'Echo in the Fog','Chapter 1: Wake Up\nRian woke up in the forest. Fog everywhere. No memory. His phone was cracked. The only message: “They’re watching.” He limped through the woods and reached a cabin. Inside—photos of him with red Xs over his face. And footsteps outside.\n\nChapter 2: Stranger’s Cabin\nThe door burst open. A girl entered—Ella. “You escaped?” she asked. “They erased your memory.” She had a notebook labeled Project Echo. Rian had no idea who he was. But the people hunting him… were still close. “Run,” she whispered.\n\nChapter 3: The Watchers\nFrom a hill, they saw men in black dragging someone through the trees. “Why are they after me?” Rian asked. Ella showed him the truth: He used to work for them. Until he found something. A video file… now hidden. “We need it,” she said.\n\nChapter 4: Memory Leak\nInside an old train station, they found a flash drive in a locker. Rian plugged it into a laptop. The footage showed: experiments on teens, memory tests, surveillance. And his face—leading it. “I did this?” he whispered. But then—BANG. The power went out.\n\nChapter 5: Trapdoor Escape\nArmed men surrounded them. Rian remembered: he created a trapdoor beneath the station floor. They dove in, barely escaping. “I was the villain,” he said. “You became the hero,” Ella replied. “Now let’s shut it down.”\n\nChapter 6: Full Recall\nThey leaked the files. The project was exposed. Teens were rescued. Rian’s memory slowly returned—but he didn’t want the old him back. The fog lifted. He wasn’t the same—but maybe that was the point. He finally remembered who he wanted to be.','ccp_36.png'),(97,1,31,'2025-06-28 19:49:50',2,'The Ember Stone','Chapter 1: The Glow in the Wall\nMira touched the old castle wall. It pulsed. A glowing ember appeared in her palm. “The Ember Stone,” whispered the librarian. “It chooses only one in a century.” That night, Mira’s dreams burned—dragons, war, and a voice: “Awaken the flame.”\n\nChapter 2: Forbidden Library\nShe followed the glow to a secret passage in the school’s basement. A dusty library with floating books. The Ember led her to a page: “Only fire can unseal the shadow door.” Mira didn’t know magic—but something inside her wanted to try.\n\nChapter 3: Fire in Her Hands\nMira focused, remembering the voice. Her fingers lit up with sparks. A hidden door opened behind the shelves. Inside—armor, maps, and a scroll with her name. “I’m in a prophecy,” she whispered. And a shadow in the mirror replied: “Yes.”\n\nChapter 4: Guardian of Ash\nFrom the ashes rose a beast—a fire fox named Ash, sworn to protect the Ember wielder. Mira touched his fur. “You must awaken the Fire Court,” Ash said. “Before the Shadows rise.” But time was running out. The mirror glowed again—showing her kingdom in flames.\n\nChapter 5: The Broken Crown\nMira reached the Fire Court, a palace buried beneath a volcano. Its rulers were turned to stone. Only the Ember could revive them. But the Shadow Queen appeared. “Give me the stone,” she hissed. Mira stood firm. “I’d rather burn.”\n\nChapter 6: Flamekeeper\nWith Ash by her side, Mira unleashed the Ember’s full light. Shadows screamed, vanishing. The Fire Court awakened, the crown restored. Mira was named Flamekeeper—the youngest in history. The ember still glows in her hand. Her journey was just beginning.','ccp_37.png'),(98,1,35,'2025-06-28 19:52:03',2,'The Whispering Woods','Chapter 1: The Tree That Spoke\nArlo wandered into the woods near his village. A tree whispered, “Help us.” He froze. Trees don’t talk… do they? The wind formed words: “The heart is dying.” Arlo didn’t understand. But he followed the sound—and vanished into the leaves.\n\nChapter 2: The Green Realm\nHe awoke in a glowing forest. Animals spoke. Flowers blinked. “You entered the Verdant Veil,” said a squirrel. “Our queen sleeps. The Heart Tree is fading.” Arlo wasn’t a hero—but he was the only human here. “What do I do?” he asked. “Listen.”\n\nChapter 3: Trials of Vine\nThe forest tested him—chasing storms, puzzles in petals, riddles from river frogs. Arlo passed each with care, not power. At last, the tree spirits gave him a seed. “Plant it in the Heart’s hollow.” But dark vines had already reached it.\n\nChapter 4: The Thorn King\nA shadow formed—half-man, half-thorn. “This world belongs to decay,” he growled. Arlo held the seed. “Life still fights,” he said. He ran, dodging the vines, and threw the seed into the Heart’s core. The Thorn King roared. Then… silence.\n\nChapter 5: Life Returns\nThe Heart Tree bloomed. Light poured through the canopy. Flowers returned. Spirits danced. The queen of the woods awakened. “You brought balance,” she said. “How?” Arlo asked. “You listened.” She smiled. “Few ever do.”\n\nChapter 6: Whispered Goodbye\nThe forest faded. Arlo opened his eyes—back home. A vine curled around his wrist, glowing faintly. In the wind, the trees whispered again. He smiled. “I hear you.” And now, he always would.','ccp_38.png'),(99,1,32,'2025-06-28 19:53:34',0,'Moonbound','Chapter 1: Marked by Light\nOn her 13th birthday, Lyra found a crescent glowing on her palm. That night, the moon called her by name. “You are Moonbound,” it whispered. Her village feared sky-magic. But Lyra felt it inside—stronger than fear. She looked up. “I’m ready.”\n\nChapter 2: The Star Map\nA stranger arrived—Caden, Starborn. He showed her a map that moved like constellations. “Each Moonbound must awaken their star,” he said. “Or darkness spreads.” Lyra followed him across floating islands and silent deserts, each night’s moon leading their way.\n\nChapter 3: Eclipse Trial\nTo awaken her star, she entered the Moon Mirror. Inside was herself—shadowed and angry. “You’re weak,” it said. Lyra stood tall. “But I’m real.” The mirror shattered. Her star ignited. Powers bloomed. Light wings. Star-blades. A true Moonbound.\n\nChapter 4: Darkfall Rises\nThe sky cracked. Creatures fell from the stars—Darkfall. “They hunt light,” Caden warned. “They fear you.” Lyra faced them with courage, holding the moonlight in her hands. “Then let them run.” She shined brighter.\n\nChapter 5: The Broken Moon\nThe moon itself dimmed. “They’re stealing it,” Caden said. Lyra flew to its surface, battling the last shadow king. He nearly broke her. But her star flared. She poured her light into the moon’s core. “Be whole again.”\n\nChapter 6: Sky Guardian\nThe sky healed. The stars sang. Lyra was crowned Sky Guardian—the youngest ever. She looked down at Earth and whispered, “Shine for them.” And the moon did. Every night. Just like her.','ccp_39.png'),(100,1,24,'2025-07-13 09:09:18',2,'The Emberleaf Prophecy','Chapter 1: Whispering Leaves\nIn Eldara’s ancient grove, the leaves never simply rustled—they whispered names. Lira, a curious orphan, wandered too close and heard her name echo from the wind-carved trunk of the Emberleaf Tree. The villagers feared the whispers, claiming they foretold impossible destinies. But Lira didn’t run. Her heart thumped in harmony with the leaves. She listened—and accepted.\n\nChapter 2: The Hidden Flame\nFollowing the whisper’s rhythm, Lira dug beneath the roots. There, buried in cool earth, flickered a small ember. It danced like it knew her. She cupped it in her hands—no heat, no burn. The ember whispered back, showing her flashes of the past and possible futures. Her eyes glowed briefly, the moment her fate ignited with magic.\n\nChapter 3: Trial of Shadows\nThat night, shadows crept into her room. Silent, dark, formless beings. The ember warned her, and she stood ready. These trials were illusions, testing her resolve. Each fear she faced twisted into forms of people she loved. But Lira whispered truth back to them. Her courage cracked their spell. At dawn, she emerged stronger, no longer afraid.\n\nChapter 4: Wings of the Wind\nTo reach the Crystal Mountains, she needed to fly. But no mortal had crossed the Zephorian cliffs. The ember summoned a storm hawk. Lira leaped from the cliff’s edge, landing on its back. Wind sang in her ears. The hawk carried her through air and thunder, where sky spirits whispered riddles she answered without fear.\n\nChapter 5: The Crystal Pact\nIn a cavern of mirrors, the Emberleaf flame pulsed. Each reflection showed a version of Lira—coward, hero, traitor, savior. She chose none. Instead, she merged with the light within. The elemental spirits appeared: earth, fire, wind, and water. She knelt. “I seek to heal, not rule.” The pact formed. The crystal on her palm gleamed.\n\nChapter 6: Prophecy Fulfilled\nReturning to Eldara, the villagers gathered in silence. The Emberleaf Tree blazed with golden fire, not destruction but rebirth. Flowers bloomed from scorched bark. “You have restored balance,” the tree whispered. Lira touched the roots. A new guardian had risen. The whispers quieted, for the prophecy had been fulfilled—and peace returned to Eldara once more.','ccp_40.png'),(101,1,26,'2025-07-13 09:11:06',3,'Crown of the Deep','Chapter 1: The Calling\nKael had never seen the ocean, but his dreams were full of waves and drowning. One night, water crept into his room—not from the sea, but from magic. Gills opened on his neck, and a glowing map formed on his wall. It pulsed like a heartbeat. Drawn by instinct, Kael followed it to the cliffs. He jumped, not falling but diving into his fate. The sea accepted him, and he swam deeper than ever thought possible, chasing the echo of his name whispered through currents. A new world awaited beneath the surface, ancient and mysterious.\n\nChapter 2: Coral Labyrinth\nThe map led Kael through forests of glowing coral and tunnels made of pearl. Murmuring fish with human eyes swam in rings, guarding silent ruins. The deeper he went, the more the sea revealed its secrets. He found symbols carved into sunken stone, echoing the shapes on his hands. Kael realized he wasn’t just exploring—he was remembering. At the center of the labyrinth, he faced a choice: open a gate sealed for centuries, or swim away forever. His hands moved on their own, unlocking the gate. A throne room lay beyond, lost to time, guarded by silence and bone.\n\nChapter 3: Leviathan’s Gift\nThe gate released more than water—it awakened the Leviathan. A monstrous creature coiled from the depths, its scales dark as sorrow. But it didn’t attack. It watched Kael with ancient eyes. Instead of fighting, Kael knelt. The Leviathan sensed his spirit and wrapped him in spiraling tendrils of memory. In return, it placed a crown on his head—woven from star coral, bone, and light. Kael could breathe without gills now, speak without sound, and hear the ocean’s true voice. The Leviathan vanished into the dark, leaving Kael empowered, changed, and ready for the tide-shaping destiny that awaited him.\n\nChapter 4: Song of Salt\nKael returned to the sunlit reefs and found them under siege. Storms ravaged the outer waters, and ships sank under blackened skies. Using his crown’s gift, he sang—not with his mouth, but from his soul. The song turned saltwater sweet and guided lost sailors home. It calmed tempests and silenced whirlpools. He became a legend, the sea’s soft hymn bringing peace. The merfolk and fishermen alike named him “The Tide Voice.” But Kael sensed a greater storm on the horizon, darker than any cloud, stirring far below the ocean floor. He had calmed the sea, but war was coming.\n\nChapter 5: Sunken War\nAbyssal witches rose from trenches, angry at the crown’s return. They summoned seaquakes and ink-dark beasts to reclaim power. Kael rallied merfolk, kelp knights, and sea dragons. The battle cracked coral towers and lit up the ocean with magic. He fought with compassion, sparing enemies who surrendered. In the end, he sealed the witches in a vortex of starlight, binding them in chains of song. The sea wept, then rejoiced. Silence fell like peace after thunder. Kael’s crown glowed with quiet pride. The depths were safe—but changed forever. The ocean, once passive, had chosen its champion. Its king.\n\nChapter 6: Rise of the Tide King\nThe Leviathan returned one final time, circling Kael in blessing. “You have earned the name,” it whispered. Kael was crowned in an ancient ceremony, surrounded by fish, spirits, and old gods of the deep. The ocean bent to him—not in fear, but in trust. He ruled not with force, but with love. Songs replaced storms. Lost ships were never lost again. And every full moon, Kael would sit on the reef’s edge, whispering to the waves, remembering the boy who jumped from cliffs into legend. The Tide King, born of prophecy, now guided the sea with steady hands.','ccp_41.png'),(102,1,9,'2025-07-13 09:13:46',2,'Mirrorthorn','Chapter 1: Reflected Eyes\nAria’s mirror blinked. Not her reflection—something else. It leaned forward, smirked, then whispered, “You don’t belong here.” Her room went cold. The reflection pressed its palm to the glass, and hers moved on its own. A pull tugged her inward. With a flash, she fell through the mirror. When she opened her eyes, she was in a world of silver light, thorny vines, and shadows that mimicked movement. She wasn’t just seeing her reflection anymore—she was walking inside it. And now, the mirrored version of her had taken her place in the real world.\n\nChapter 2: Silver Forest\nThe mirrored world was twisted. Trees were metallic, leaves shimmered like blades, and time moved oddly—faster in footsteps, slower in thoughts. Aria wandered through a silver forest where sound echoed long after it ended. Every time she called for help, her voice returned older, broken, strange. Creatures of glass slithered beneath roots, whispering secrets she didn’t understand. Eventually, she found a cracked mirror embedded in an ancient tree. Inside it, her real-world self laughed cruelly. “Your life fits better on me,” it mocked. Aria knew this place wasn’t just magic—it was hunger, and it wanted her to stay.\n\nChapter 3: The Glass Beast\nThe sky fractured as a creature made of shattered glass emerged. It moved like a memory breaking—jagged, fast, and filled with regret. The beast chased Aria through forests that reshaped behind her, always cutting off escape. But Aria noticed it didn’t bleed—it reflected. So she tricked it. She found a calm pool, faced her fear, and stood still. The beast lunged—only to collide with its own reflection. It shattered with a scream, shards raining like silver snow. Aria collected a piece. It pulsed with warmth. In that fragment, she saw herself—not broken, but bold. Her journey had just begun.\n\nChapter 4: Memory Pool\nShe arrived at the Pool of Remembering, where water mirrored your truth. When she looked in, she saw fragments—her mother’s lullabies, her first heartbreak, her last smile before entering this realm. Each memory hovered like stars above the pool. Then came ones she didn’t recognize: her birth in this mirrored world, her parents—two versions, one light, one shadow. Aria realized she wasn’t just stolen—she was born of both realms. Half human, half mirrorborn. Accepting this truth lit her heart. She drank from the pool, and her vision cleared. For the first time, she knew who she really was.\n\nChapter 5: Shatterheart\nTo escape the mirrored prison, Aria had to destroy the Heart Mirror—the source of all reflection-based life. But doing so would erase her mirrored half. Still, she couldn’t let the false Aria steal her world. In the Mirror Hall, surrounded by infinite versions of herself, she chose unity over rejection. She embraced her duality, shattering the Heart Mirror not in rage—but in understanding. Light exploded. Her mirrored self cried out, then softened. They fused—not lost, but whole. Aria stepped forward with both sides within her. She wasn’t just a girl. She was a bridge between reflections and reality.\n\nChapter 6: Keeper of Realms\nNow free, Aria returned to her world. People stared, sensing something changed. The old mirror in her room now held no reflection—only depth. She had become the Keeper, guardian of the fragile veil between realities. Whenever a mirror trembled or someone saw something strange in glass, it was her watching, protecting. She kept balance between truth and illusion. Sometimes, she visited the mirrored forest in dreams, where creatures still whispered. But she never feared them again. For now, Aria walked both worlds, reflection and flesh in harmony. And no one would ever steal her place again.','ccp_42.png'),(103,1,27,'2025-07-13 09:16:16',1,'The Skyborn Alchemist','Chapter 1: Ash in the Wind\nOrin lived in a crumbling tower, where inventions sparked but always failed. His neighbors mocked him, calling him “the Tin Fool.” One day, ash fell from the sky—not from fire, but from clouds. The ash shimmered, singing as it drifted. Orin bottled some, curious. That night, he dreamed of flying cities and voices whispering forgotten names. When he awoke, a gear on his table spun on its own. He knew then: the ash wasn’t ash. It was a calling card, a message from the sky. Something above wanted him to build again—but this time, it would work.\n\nChapter 2: Skyroot Elixir\nOrin experimented with the ash, mixing it with roots from the sky-growing tree in his courtyard. The liquid glowed, fizzing gently. Hesitant, he drank it. His body lifted, light as steam. His boots rose from the floor, and he hovered, eyes wide. He could feel currents of air like threads he could pull. The world below shrank. With a laugh and a shout, he soared into the clouds. Through storms and rays, he flew higher than birds. Above the tallest peaks, he saw floating islands made of crystal and copper—ancient, impossible cities forgotten by the world below.\n\nChapter 3: Cloudforge\nLanding on one of the sky isles, Orin discovered Cloudforge, a city powered by thunder and willpower. Machines floated effortlessly, fueled by stormstone cores. He found books written in wind, blueprints carved into lightning. Skyborn alchemists greeted him cautiously. “You carry the ash of recall,” said their leader, an elder with a voice like thunder. Orin learned their craft—alchemy that shaped clouds, bottled lightning, and forged wings from wind. He crafted boots that responded to thought, gloves that bent the air. For the first time, Orin belonged. He wasn’t a fool anymore. He was an alchemist of the skies.\n\nChapter 4: Airborne Duel\nBut not all Skyborn welcomed him. A rogue alchemist, Veera, saw his presence as a threat. “The sky isn’t for outsiders,” she hissed. She summoned a storm hawk made of blades. Orin dodged midair, using his gloves to shift wind. He summoned a cloud net, but it failed. Then he remembered: lightning is memory. He shaped a bolt from regret—his failures, his loneliness—and hurled it. It struck Veera’s hawk, dissolving it. She fell—but Orin caught her. “Even storms can change course,” he said. She stared at him, stunned. Respect earned, not by power—but by mercy.\n\nChapter 5: Broken Wings\nWhile experimenting, Orin pushed his wings too far. They cracked midflight, sending him tumbling through storms. Lightning slashed past as he fell toward the mountains. In those moments, he thought of every failure. But his mind didn’t surrender—it worked faster. He used his gloves to condense air into a soft pocket, breaking his fall. Bones bruised, pride shaken, he rebuilt. This time, he wove skyroot into the frame and sealed the joints with ash. The wings were stronger, quieter. He didn’t fly just for glory anymore. He flew because he was meant to rise, fall, and rise again.\n\nChapter 6: The Ascendant\nThe Skyborn gathered beneath an eclipse. A vote was cast—not by popularity, but by invention. Orin’s name echoed through the clouds. The elder stepped forward and handed him the title: Ascendant. He bowed, not as a king, but a learner. Now, Orin teaches others—earthborn and skyborn alike. The floating cities no longer hide. He shaped bridges of wind between worlds. In every village below, ash sometimes falls from the sky, gentle and glowing. It’s a whisper of hope, a call to build, to dream. Somewhere above, Orin flies still—an alchemist who turned failure into flight, and clouds into home.','ccp_43.png'),(104,1,4,'2025-07-13 09:18:12',0,'Thornspell','Chapter 1: The Cursed Garden\nElenore stepped into the garden only once—but that was enough. Roses taller than towers bloomed in silence. Each petal shimmered like velvet, but their thorns bled ink, not sap. She plucked one. A sting—then silence. Her memories faded instantly: her name, her past, her purpose. All gone. The garden whispered, promising beauty in return for memory. But something deeper inside her screamed to fight it. Elenore dropped the rose, knelt among the vines, and whispered her name aloud. The garden trembled. Somewhere in its roots, it remembered her too. The curse had a weakness—and she had just awakened it.\n\nChapter 2: Thorns of Time\nThe garden warped with every step she took. One direction led to childhood, another to forgotten years. Each thorn she touched gave back fragments: laughter by a lakeside, a mother’s voice, the cold grip of betrayal. But nothing stayed. To reclaim herself, she needed the Rose of Time—hidden in the garden’s heart. Creatures made of vine and sorrow blocked her way, but they hesitated. “You’re not like the others,” they hissed. She pressed forward, forging a path through living memories. At the garden’s core, she found a gate of silver brambles. Beyond it, time stood still—waiting to be unbound.\n\nChapter 3: Bloom of Truth\nInside the silver brambles, a single flower floated—neither dead nor alive. The Rose of Time. Elenore reached out, but the rose pulled her mind into its petals. She relived everything—her first love, her deepest shame, and the secret she had buried even from herself. She had chosen to enter the garden once before... to forget. The rose showed her why: to protect a secret so powerful, even she couldn’t hold it. But now, she remembered. With tears falling, she plucked the bloom. The garden howled as the truth broke free. Elenore no longer feared it. She embraced it.\n\nChapter 4: The Forgotten Prince\nAt the garden’s center lay a figure entangled in roots—eyes shut, heart still. The prince, long forgotten by the world. He had traded his memories for hers, centuries ago, to save her life. Elenore knelt, pressing the Rose of Time to his chest. The petals sank into him. His eyes fluttered open, golden and ancient. “You came back,” he said. She remembered him now—every secret smile, every silent promise. The garden hissed in fury. Together, they stood, hand in hand, facing the thorns that rose like waves. “Let it come,” Elenore whispered. “We’ve lived enough in silence.”\n\nChapter 5: Petal War\nThe garden attacked. Vines lashed like whips. Roses bloomed like bombs. Elenore summoned memory magic; the prince wielded light from forgotten stars. Every emotion became a weapon—love formed shields, sorrow bent thorns away, laughter scattered petals into weapons of light. They fought not to destroy, but to reclaim. Each fallen flower released a captive memory. The garden shrieked, unraveling itself. At its center, the true curse lay—a seed of grief planted by a broken sorceress long ago. Elenore touched it gently. “You are not alone anymore,” she said. The seed cracked. From it bloomed a flower of hope.\n\nChapter 6: The New Garden\nThe old garden withered. In its place bloomed a field of untainted roses—gentle, bright, alive. Elenore and the prince replanted the land together, using soil laced with truth and petals born from healing. Now, when travelers wandered close, the garden gave memories instead of taking them. It whispered names, offered dreams, and let people remember who they were. Elenore became its guardian, no longer cursed but crowned in petals. She smiled often, for the past no longer hurt—it bloomed. The prince remained by her side, his memory whole. They had conquered the thorns. Now, only beauty remained.','ccp_44.png'),(105,4,24,'2025-07-20 15:09:27',2,'C.A.T. – Crimson Alley Terrors','Chapter 1: The First Scratch\nDetective Mara found the victim slashed open in Crimson Alley. No footprints. No weapon. Just a single black cat staring from the shadows. Its eyes glowed unnaturally red. “Coincidence?” her partner joked. Mara didn’t laugh. She felt watched.\n\nChapter 2: The Vanished Witness\nAn old man claimed the cat walked upright, whispering names before the murders. “Cursed, that thing is.” Hours later, his apartment burned. Nothing left but ash—and a pawprint burned into the wall. Mara reviewed footage. The cat was smiling.\n\nChapter 3: Nine Lives\nThe cat appeared at every crime scene. Mara fired at it once. The bullet passed through. “Maybe it’s a hallucination,” her partner said. Then he was found dead—gutted. A note in his mouth read: “Eight lives left, Detective.”\n\nChapter 4: The Crimson File\nDigging deeper, Mara found an old file: nine victims, all linked to a cover-up. The first investigator died mysteriously—his last note said, “The cat knows.” Each new victim matched the list. Mara’s name was next. The cat purred nearby.\n\nChapter 5: The Trap\nMara staged a fake crime to lure the creature. Midnight struck. The cat emerged, eyes blazing. “You can’t hide the truth,” it hissed. Her trap failed. It moved like smoke, claws slicing air. “Justice has claws,” it whispered.\n\nChapter 6: The Final Life\nBleeding, Mara confessed everything—her role in the cover-up. “I was young. Scared.” The cat stopped. “Guilt is a leash,” it said. It vanished. Days passed. No more murders. But every night, Mara sees glowing eyes watching her sleep. Waiting.','ccp_45.png'),(106,4,38,'2025-07-20 15:27:53',6,'C.I.R.C.L.E. – Criminals In Rituals, Cursed Lives Ended','Chapter 1: The Pact\nSix strangers formed a secret group: C.I.R.C.L.E., bound by a blood ritual after a perfect crime. No evidence. No witnesses. They walked free. But on the anniversary, one member was found—charred, twisted in a circle. The message: “Balance must return.”\n\nChapter 2: Blood Pattern\nDetective Reza found another—drained of blood, body arranged in the same perfect circle. Each had burned markings. Only she noticed the strange emblem etched near them. The survivors refused to talk. “We ended it,” one cried. “Why is it back?”\n\nChapter 3: Whispers\nSurvivors reported haunting visions—black smoke, chanting, and a pale child drawing circles in ash. “She’s back,” one whispered before his body combusted. Reza\'s phone buzzed. Unknown number. One word: “Four.” That night, she dreamed of standing inside a burning ring.\n\nChapter 4: The Fourth Flame\nThe fourth died in a church—body hanging upside down in a flaming circle of candles. No alarms triggered. CCTV showed static... and then her own face. Reza felt sick. “What if I’m part of this?” she asked herself. “Chosen?”\n\nChapter 5: The Original Sin\nThe last two met her in secret. “We summoned something that night,” they admitted. “A spirit tied to justice and symmetry.” Reza pressed them. “What did you do?” One replied, shaking: “We sacrificed an innocent. Her curse is the circle.”\n\nChapter 6: Completion\nThe last two died together—burned into a spiral of symbols. Reza stared at her reflection—her eyes now glowed faintly. The circle was complete, and she was marked. She didn’t scream. She just whispered, “Who’s next?” And somewhere, the cycle restarted.','ccp_46.png'),(107,4,33,'2025-07-20 15:36:13',5,'E.Y.E.S. – Every Year Evil Strikes','Chapter 1: Found Again\nEvery year, on July 13th, one person vanishes. This time, it’s a judge—found hanging from a tree, eyelids removed. “E.Y.E.S.” carved into his chest. Detective Lina whispers, “Same mark. Same day.” The town trembles. The Eye Killer is back.\n\nChapter 2: Silent Witness\nA teen survivor claims she saw the killer—faceless, with eyes all over its body. “He doesn’t blink,” she sobs. The power cuts out. In the dark, her screams echo. Lights return. She’s gone. Only a bloody eyeball remains.\n\nChapter 3: Archived\nOld files show E.Y.E.S. began five years ago—each victim tied to a sealed corruption case. Lina finds her father’s name in one. He was a cop. He vanished in ‘21. Her hands shake. She’s not just hunting the killer—she’s involved.\n\nChapter 4: Red Reflection\nLina sees eyes in mirrors—dozens, watching. Her camera glitches. When she develops the photos, her reflection is missing. A note is taped to her wall: “Truth sees truth.” Her ceiling drips red. She checks—no pipes. Just a blinking eye above.\n\nChapter 5: Judgment\nShe digs into her father’s case—he helped bury a child abuse ring. All victims connected to that trial. Lina was a child back then. A survivor. That night, she dreams of fire and ash... and the faceless figure staring down.\n\nChapter 6: Eye for Eye\nOn July 13th, Lina enters the old courthouse, following the eyes drawn in blood. The killer stands inside—wearing no face, only eyes. “It’s your turn,” he says. She doesn’t scream. She steps forward. “Then I’ll be your justice.” The lights flicker.','ccp_1.png'),(108,1,33,'2025-07-20 15:38:39',4,'F.A.T.E. – Forest of Ancients, Trials Eternal','Chapter 1: The Invitation\nOn her sixteenth birthday, Lyra receives a letter sealed with gold bark. “You’ve been chosen by F.A.T.E.” That night, the forest calls her name. Her grandmother gasps. “No one ever returns unchanged.” Lyra steps into the glowing, whispering trees.\n\nChapter 2: Trial One – The Echo\nThe trees reflect Lyra’s thoughts. Every lie she’s told echoes around her in familiar voices. Her guilt takes shape—a shadowy twin. It attacks with truths. She faces herself, screaming. “I’m not weak!” The shadow bows. The forest hums approval.\n\nChapter 3: Trial Two – The Flame\nA burning village appears. Lyra sees her parents begging for help. She runs to them—but the fire consumes her arms. “This is illusion,” she says, resisting. The fire vanishes. Ashes in her hand turn into a glowing phoenix feather.\n\nChapter 4: Trial Three – The Choice\nShe finds two paths: one to infinite power, one to forgotten peace. A spirit says, “You may not return the same.” Lyra hesitates, then chooses the harder trail. “I want to remember. I want to fight.” The spirit smiles. She passes.\n\nChapter 5: The Ancient Throne\nAt the forest’s heart stands a living throne made of root and bone. It pulses with every step she takes. “Name your wish,” it says. Lyra kneels. “I wish to protect others from losing themselves.” The throne dissolves—into her.\n\nChapter 6: Return of the Chosen\nLyra walks back into the village, eyes glowing with forest light. Trees bloom behind her. No one recognizes her—but they bow. “The F.A.T.E. has spoken,” says the elder. She smiles softly. She remembers everything. The forest lives within her now.','ccp_2.png'),(109,1,34,'2025-07-20 15:40:30',1,'S.H.A.D.E. – Silent Heir And the Dusk Eclipse','Chapter 1: Marked by Dusk\nEira was born during a solar eclipse—silent, pale, with crescent markings on her palm. The villagers whispered, “Cursed.” On her eighteenth eclipse, the moon bled red. Shadows gathered around her bed. A voice whispered, “It’s time to return, heir.”\n\nChapter 2: The Door Beneath\nIn the forest, a door of smoke appeared beneath an old willow. Her mark glowed. “Open it,” said the wind. She stepped through and entered a kingdom cast in twilight—ruled by silence and long-lost memories of her bloodline.\n\nChapter 3: The Silent Court\nGhostlike nobles bowed. “Princess Eira, you return.” She couldn’t speak—the realm had stolen her voice. A shadow creature approached. “Your words were sealed when the eclipse took your mother.” He handed her a blade made of moonlight. “Reclaim your throne.”\n\nChapter 4: Trials of Shadow\nTo speak again, Eira faced three trials: stillness, memory, and mercy. In stillness, she calmed a storm. In memory, she watched her mother’s death. In mercy, she spared a traitor’s ghost. Her voice returned, not as sound—but as command.\n\nChapter 5: The Eclipse Crown\nThe moon darkened once more. Eira climbed the Shadow Spire. The eclipse crowned her with silver flame. “You are duskborn—made of balance,” the realm chanted. Light and shadow merged within her eyes. The throne pulsed. Peace began to stir again.\n\nChapter 6: The Whispering Queen\nBack in her world, Eira spoke softly—and the earth listened. Storms stilled, wolves bowed, and night obeyed. Her voice wasn’t loud, but it was law. Once cursed, now crowned. Every eclipse, a whisper passes through kingdoms: Beware the queen who rules in shade.','ccp_3.png'),(110,1,31,'2025-07-20 15:42:27',3,'??? ????????’? ??????????','Chapter 1: ???????? ?? ??? ????\nSylva hears the forest calling, voices older than time. A silver wisp guides her path to the heart of Faerie. “You are chosen,” it hums. With each step, her bond with the wild deepens—ancient magic awakens in her veins.\n\nChapter 2: ? ???? ??????\nAt the Faerie Court, Sylva discovers she descends from the last Wisp Queen. Her powers are bound by secrets and shadows. To claim her legacy, she must embrace the unseen—and the dangers lurking beneath the silver leaves.\n\nChapter 3: ??? ???????? ?? ???????\nA curse silences the forest’s heart. Sylva must find the source—a dark spirit feeding on whispered fears. She learns to speak with shadows, unraveling lies and forging alliances with creatures of light and dark.\n\nChapter 4: ????? ?? ?????\nStorm clouds gather as the balance tips. Sylva’s magic flares, calling faeries and spirits to her side. The court prepares for war—not just for the forest, but for the fate of worlds intertwined.\n\nChapter 5: ????? ?? ?????\nIn a luminous glade, Sylva dances beneath stars, weaving spells of protection and hope. She embraces her role as Whisperer, guiding lost souls and calming the wild’s restless heart.\n\nChapter 6: ???????? ??? ???? ????\nSylva’s voice restores the forest’s song. The Faerie realm blooms anew, shimmering with light and shadow in perfect harmony. She reigns, guardian of whispers and wild magic—forever the bridge between worlds.','ccp_4.png'),(111,1,30,'2025-07-20 15:44:43',1,'The Scarlet Throne','Chapter 1: ??? ????????\nKaelen’s village burns, flames licking the sky. From the ashes, a crimson crown appears—calling him. His touch ignites embers in his veins. “You are the heir of the Flameborn,” a voice booms. The fire chooses its king.\n\nChapter 2: ????’? ?????\nKaelen faces the Trial of Ashes, walking through fire without fear. Each step awakens powers and burns old fears. Sparks dance on his skin; he learns to wield flame—not just as destruction, but as life.\n\nChapter 3: ??????? ???????\nEnemies rise—shadowy figures jealous of his power. Kaelen’s flame battles darkness, a war of heat and shadow. The scarlet crown pulses, warning him: power alone won’t save a kingdom.\n\nChapter 4: ????? ?? ???????\nFriends rally—mages, warriors, and fire spirits. Kaelen leads them through burning lands, forging bonds stronger than steel. The fire within bonds them; their loyalty is a flame unbreakable.\n\nChapter 5: ??? ???? ?????\nA traitor’s smoke blinds Kaelen, threatening to snuff out his flame. Betrayal burns deeper than fire. In the darkest hour, Kaelen finds strength in forgiveness—and the fire within grows fiercer.\n\nChapter 6: ?????? ?????\nThe scarlet crown glows brighter than ever. Kaelen stands atop the throne, flame roaring in his heart. Kingdoms unite under his light. Fire renews all—destruction and creation intertwined. The Flameborn reigns eternal.','ccp_5.png'),(112,2,30,'2025-07-20 15:47:06',2,'V.E.I.L. – Vanished, Enigmas, & Invisible Lies','Chapter 1: The Disappearance\nDetective Mara arrives at the abandoned mansion where the mayor vanished without a trace. No signs of struggle, no clues—only a cryptic note: “The veil will lift.” Shadows flicker in the empty halls. Someone is watching.\n\nChapter 2: Hidden Messages\nIn the mayor’s study, Mara finds encoded letters hidden beneath wallpaper. Each reveals parts of a secret meeting—one that never happened. As she deciphers the code, the mansion’s lights flicker. Whispers echo: “You’re too close.”\n\nChapter 3: The Silent Witness\nA mute gardener saw a stranger leaving the mansion night of the disappearance. Mara trusts his eyes more than words. The gardener sketches the stranger’s face—a masked figure. Suddenly, his hut burns down. The veil of silence grows thicker.\n\nChapter 4: Double Shadows\nMara uncovers a second note—this one warns her to stop digging. Her partner disappears. She suspects a mole inside the force. Trust erodes. The masked figure’s identity remains a puzzle. The veil tightens; the shadows lengthen.\n\nChapter 5: The Breaking Point\nTrapped in a cat-and-mouse game, Mara follows a trail to an underground chamber. There, she confronts the mastermind behind the veil—a person she once trusted. The truth twists like a knife. Lies crumble. Only one secret remains: why the mayor vanished.\n\nChapter 6: Lift the Veil\nMara exposes the conspiracy. The veil is lifted—but the aftermath is chaos. The mayor’s fate revealed shocks the city. As Mara walks away, she knows some lies are invisible for a reason. The veil might close again—waiting for the next seeker.','ccp_6.png'),(113,2,27,'2025-07-20 15:48:43',1,'Secrets In Layers, Every Night Cloaks Everything','Chapter 1: Vanishing Point\nJournalist Ava investigates the sudden disappearance of a famous author. His last manuscript vanished too. His apartment is spotless, except a cryptic symbol drawn in blood. Ava senses someone watching. The silence in the city feels heavy, almost alive.\n\nChapter 2: Layers Unfold\nAva decodes the symbol—a key to an underground society. She uncovers layers of lies hidden beneath the author’s success. Contacts disappear. Messages self-destruct. Her every move is shadowed. The deeper she digs, the louder the silence screams.\n\nChapter 3: Night Watch\nStrange noises haunt Ava’s apartment. She installs cameras, but footage shows empty rooms. At midnight, a figure appears—always just out of focus. Friends warn her to stop. “Some secrets,” they say, “are meant to sleep forever.” Ava can’t turn back.\n\nChapter 4: Cloaked Truths\nAn informant reveals a secret meeting in the city’s catacombs. Ava attends, disguised. Shadows exchange envelopes and threats. The author’s fate is sealed by those who control the narrative. Ava’s identity is compromised. Escape is no longer an option.\n\nChapter 5: Breaking Silence\nAva leaks evidence to the public, triggering panic. Powerful figures retaliate. She’s chased through dark alleys, betrayed by those closest to her. A final message appears on her phone: “Silence will kill you.” Ava prepares to face the silence head-on.\n\nChapter 6: Echoes\nThe truth shatters illusions but awakens darker forces. Ava disappears into the night, her story unfinished. The city breathes again, but silence lingers. Whispers say she vanished into the layers of secrets, becoming one with the silence she fought to break.','ccp_7.png'),(114,3,27,'2025-07-20 15:50:17',1,'Discovering Realities, Embracing All Magic','Chapter 1: The Unexpected Letter\nMaya finds a mysterious letter in her locker, inviting her to join the D.R.E.A.M. academy. Confused but curious, she decides to go. The school looks normal—but whispers of magic ripple through the halls. Maya’s ordinary life is about to change forever.\n\nChapter 2: New Friends, New Rules\nAt D.R.E.A.M., Maya meets Leo and Iris—both hiding secrets. Classes teach strange subjects like “Time Weaving” and “Dream Crafting.” Rules seem strict but fair. Maya struggles to keep up but feels something deep inside awakening. This is just the beginning.\n\nChapter 3: The First Test\nStudents face the Trial of Shadows, confronting fears made real. Maya’s shadow takes the shape of loneliness. With help from friends, she learns courage isn’t absence of fear—it’s acting despite it. The test ends, but questions linger. What’s truly lurking in dreams?\n\nChapter 4: Secrets Unveiled\nMaya discovers a hidden library with books that rewrite themselves. She learns D.R.E.A.M. was founded centuries ago by youth with magical gifts. Some students vanish mysteriously. Maya vows to uncover the truth before she’s next. Trust becomes her most valuable magic.\n\nChapter 5: The Dream Thief\nA shadowy figure steals dreams, leaving students trapped in endless sleep. Maya, Leo, and Iris follow clues into the Dreamscape, a world between worlds. They confront the thief, a lost student consumed by fear. Only together can they save their friends.\n\nChapter 6: Awake and Unbroken\nBack in reality, the school is safe—for now. Maya realizes magic isn’t just spells or dreams, but friendship, bravery, and hope. The letter was an invitation, but the real journey is just starting. She smiles: her dream is real.','ccp_8.png');
